WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.567 --> 00:00:01.501
The Vice President:
Well, good morning,

00:00:01.501 --> 00:00:02.936
and thank you all for being here
for the second meeting

00:00:02.936 --> 00:00:04.237
of the National Space Council.

00:00:04.237 --> 00:00:06.005
I want to thank all of
the members who are here,

00:00:06.005 --> 00:00:07.607
the members of our
user advisory group,

00:00:07.607 --> 00:00:09.876
and all of those
who have taken time

00:00:09.876 --> 00:00:13.079
to join us in person and online.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:15.315
We'll go ahead
and get started.

00:00:15.315 --> 00:00:17.684
Today, we have two panel
discussions on the challenges

00:00:17.684 --> 00:00:19.819
and opportunities facing
our national security,

00:00:20.553 --> 00:00:22.489
and commercial space activities

00:00:22.489 --> 00:00:25.158
that I just spoke about
in my opening remarks.

00:00:25.892 --> 00:00:26.726
We're pleased to be joined

00:00:26.726 --> 00:00:29.929
by an outstanding lineup
of expert witnesses

00:00:29.929 --> 00:00:32.565
who will share their
insights and expertise

00:00:32.565 --> 00:00:35.001
with the Council
in the moments ahead.

00:00:35.602 --> 00:00:38.338
But first off, I'd like to ask
some of the Council members

00:00:38.338 --> 00:00:40.974
to provide updates
on the progress that we've made

00:00:40.974 --> 00:00:42.342
since our first
meeting to implement

00:00:42.342 --> 00:00:45.044
President Trump's vision for
American leadership in space.

00:00:46.546 --> 00:00:49.516
I'm going to begin with our
National Security Advisor,

00:00:50.083 --> 00:00:51.718
General H.R. McMaster.

00:00:51.718 --> 00:00:54.187
General, I want to commend
you first and foremost

00:00:54.187 --> 00:00:55.789
and the National Security Agency

00:00:56.656 --> 00:01:00.593
for your efforts in support of
the National Space Council.

00:01:01.661 --> 00:01:04.531
I specifically want to thank
the General Bill Likery

00:01:04.531 --> 00:01:06.366
of the National Security Council

00:01:06.366 --> 00:01:09.869
for his extraordinary work on
the space strategic framework.

00:01:09.869 --> 00:01:11.304
Could you please
give the Council

00:01:11.304 --> 00:01:13.306
an overview of that work?

00:01:15.308 --> 00:01:16.676
General McMaster:
Thank you Mr. Vice President,

00:01:16.676 --> 00:01:18.111
and thank you
for the opportunity

00:01:18.111 --> 00:01:20.847
to provide an update
on the important progress

00:01:20.847 --> 00:01:24.384
we have made in developing
the new strategy for space,

00:01:24.384 --> 00:01:25.819
and I want to thank,
first of all,

00:01:25.819 --> 00:01:27.654
fellow Council members here

00:01:27.654 --> 00:01:29.355
for their
tremendous collaboration

00:01:29.956 --> 00:01:31.591
and teamwork.

00:01:31.591 --> 00:01:33.126
As you noted,
Mr. Vice President,

00:01:33.126 --> 00:01:35.428
at the last Space Council
meeting in October

00:01:36.196 --> 00:01:38.998
you approved the strategic
framework for the new strategy,

00:01:38.998 --> 00:01:41.301
and I thought it might be
useful for our audience

00:01:41.301 --> 00:01:44.037
to briefly summarize
that framework

00:01:44.037 --> 00:01:46.639
and what we've done with
that framework since then.

00:01:48.174 --> 00:01:52.679
As a reminder, the framework
contained three key elements.

00:01:53.379 --> 00:01:58.218
First, it defined
our vital interests in space

00:01:58.218 --> 00:02:01.721
to ensure unfettered
access to and freedom

00:02:01.721 --> 00:02:04.624
to operate in the space domain,

00:02:05.325 --> 00:02:08.995
to advance the security,
economic prosperity,

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:13.166
and scientific knowledge
of the nation.

00:02:13.166 --> 00:02:17.604
Second, it set a desired
end state for the new strategy

00:02:17.604 --> 00:02:19.606
to ensure U.S. leadership,

00:02:20.139 --> 00:02:24.143
preeminence, and freedom 
of action in space

00:02:24.143 --> 00:02:26.613
for decades to come.

00:02:26.613 --> 00:02:29.883
And finally, it outlined
four strategic objectives

00:02:29.883 --> 00:02:31.718
in pursuit of our
vital interests.

00:02:32.285 --> 00:02:36.589
They are, first, to strengthen
the safety, stability,

00:02:36.589 --> 00:02:39.959
and sustainability
of space activities.

00:02:39.959 --> 00:02:43.796
Second, to deter and,
when necessary,

00:02:43.796 --> 00:02:47.901
defeat adversary space
and counter-space threats

00:02:48.668 --> 00:02:51.304
that are hostile to
the national interests

00:02:51.304 --> 00:02:54.440
of the United States
and our allies.

00:02:55.475 --> 00:02:58.778
Third, to partner with
the U.S. commercial sector

00:02:59.379 --> 00:03:02.048
to ensure that American
companies remain

00:03:02.048 --> 00:03:03.249
the leading providers

00:03:03.249 --> 00:03:07.053
of traditional and innovative
space technologies,

00:03:07.053 --> 00:03:10.557
goods, and services on
the international space market.

00:03:11.324 --> 00:03:16.663
And fourth, to maintain
and extend U.S. human presence

00:03:17.263 --> 00:03:20.934
and robotic explorations
beyond Earth,

00:03:20.934 --> 00:03:23.369
to transform knowledge
of ourselves,

00:03:24.037 --> 00:03:28.207
the planet, our solar system,
and the universe.

00:03:29.208 --> 00:03:31.878
So, since October, at your
direction, Mr. Vice President,

00:03:31.878 --> 00:03:33.980
we have developed
the lines of effort

00:03:34.881 --> 00:03:36.549
and identified the specific

00:03:36.549 --> 00:03:40.453
associated tasks to meet
the strategic objectives,

00:03:40.453 --> 00:03:42.088
achieve our desired end state,

00:03:42.622 --> 00:03:44.724
and advance our vital
interests in space.

00:03:45.525 --> 00:03:48.661
The four interrelated
lines of effort are,

00:03:49.395 --> 00:03:51.898
first, mission assurance.

00:03:52.832 --> 00:03:55.335
We will accelerate
the transformation

00:03:55.335 --> 00:03:57.203
of our space architecture

00:03:57.203 --> 00:04:00.340
by deliberately moving systems
from science and technology

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:03.242
phase to research 
and development phase,

00:04:03.242 --> 00:04:05.945
to actual fielding
of capabilities.

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:08.915
As a result, our space systems
will be more resilient,

00:04:09.582 --> 00:04:12.652
more defendable,
more easily reconstituted,

00:04:13.219 --> 00:04:14.754
and better service to orbit.

00:04:15.722 --> 00:04:19.826
Our second line of effort is
on deterrence and war fighting.

00:04:20.827 --> 00:04:22.762
Due to competitor
and adversary actions,

00:04:22.762 --> 00:04:25.999
the space domain is
increasingly contested.

00:04:26.633 --> 00:04:29.669
Space has now joined land, sea,

00:04:29.669 --> 00:04:32.639
and air as a war
fighting domain.

00:04:32.639 --> 00:04:35.475
While we prefer the conflict
not extend to space,

00:04:36.042 --> 00:04:39.379
the United States will be
prepared if it does.

00:04:40.179 --> 00:04:42.782
Our third line of effort
is on organizational support.

00:04:43.416 --> 00:04:45.318
We will pursue
improved foundational

00:04:45.318 --> 00:04:47.253
capabilities, structures,

00:04:47.253 --> 00:04:51.124
and processes to enable
more effective space operations.

00:04:51.691 --> 00:04:53.292
And our fourth and final line
of effort

00:04:53.292 --> 00:04:56.929
focuses on conducive
environments,

00:04:56.929 --> 00:04:57.964
both at home and abroad.

00:04:57.964 --> 00:05:00.166
As you mentioned
in your opening remarks,

00:05:00.166 --> 00:05:01.768
Mr. Vice President,
we have work to do.

00:05:02.368 --> 00:05:04.604
Domestically,
this includes streamlining

00:05:05.104 --> 00:05:06.639
the regulatory environment

00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:10.009
to better use
and support U.S. industry.

00:05:10.009 --> 00:05:13.379
Internationally, this includes
pursuing bilateral

00:05:13.379 --> 00:05:14.914
and multilateral engagements

00:05:15.448 --> 00:05:16.949
to enable human exploration,

00:05:17.583 --> 00:05:19.385
promote burden sharing,

00:05:19.385 --> 00:05:21.454
and foster cooperation

00:05:21.454 --> 00:05:25.391
against threatening
adversary space actions.

00:05:25.391 --> 00:05:28.428
Mr. Vice President,
like our audience today

00:05:28.428 --> 00:05:30.997
and like the panels
that you'll see here today,

00:05:32.198 --> 00:05:35.368
these efforts cut across
national security,

00:05:35.368 --> 00:05:38.071
commercial,
and civil space sectors,

00:05:38.905 --> 00:05:41.441
and the strategy
will not only advance

00:05:41.441 --> 00:05:44.377
the benefits of space
for ourselves,

00:05:44.377 --> 00:05:47.113
but also ensure that
peoples of all nations

00:05:47.613 --> 00:05:51.384
can benefit from the tremendous
potential that space offers.

00:05:51.984 --> 00:05:53.619
I should note that
the President's recent

00:05:53.619 --> 00:05:54.387
budget submission,

00:05:54.387 --> 00:05:55.988
since Mick Mulvaney's not here:

00:05:55.988 --> 00:06:00.893
it increases the funding
for DOD space programs

00:06:00.893 --> 00:06:05.531
by over $1 billion
in fiscal year 2019 alone,

00:06:05.531 --> 00:06:08.301
and by eight billion
over the next five years.

00:06:08.301 --> 00:06:13.172
NASA's budget for 2019 is being
increased by 300 million,

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:18.211
while also being restructured
to focus more on exploration.

00:06:18.945 --> 00:06:20.680
With your endorsement,
Mr. Vice President

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:22.215
and the President's approval,

00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:24.150
we are prepared
to begin implementing

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:25.952
this national
strategy for space,

00:06:26.886 --> 00:06:32.024
and periodically assess progress
and recommend adjustments

00:06:32.024 --> 00:06:34.494
to you and to the Council
and the President.

00:06:35.061 --> 00:06:36.395
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

00:06:36.395 --> 00:06:38.598
The Vice President:
Great, thank you General,

00:06:38.598 --> 00:06:41.000
and thank you for
the great collaboration

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:42.735
between the National
Space Council

00:06:42.735 --> 00:06:44.670
and the National
Security Council.

00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:45.972
It's been seamless,

00:06:45.972 --> 00:06:51.944
and we appreciate your update
for this meeting.

00:06:52.812 --> 00:06:55.648
The acting administrator
of NASA, Robert Lightfoot,

00:06:57.884 --> 00:07:01.187
has been busy implementing
the space policy directive

00:07:01.187 --> 00:07:06.192
and also that direction
from the President,

00:07:06.759 --> 00:07:09.395
guided the development of the
President's budget submission.

00:07:11.164 --> 00:07:12.632
Perhaps you could give us

00:07:12.632 --> 00:07:14.133
a brief overview

00:07:14.133 --> 00:07:15.368
of the budget presentation,

00:07:15.368 --> 00:07:16.736
and the implementation
of the directive.

00:07:18.004 --> 00:07:19.038
Administrator Lightfoot:
Will do.

00:07:19.038 --> 00:07:21.140
Thank you, Mr. Vice President
and fellow Council members,

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:22.475
especially those of you
that worked with us

00:07:22.475 --> 00:07:25.645
on this development
of this answer and action

00:07:25.645 --> 00:07:27.413
to the space policy
directive one.

00:07:28.414 --> 00:07:31.484
What we did in developing
this initiative

00:07:31.484 --> 00:07:33.719
was we came up with what we call
the Exploration Campaign.

00:07:34.887 --> 00:07:38.291
This Exploration Campaign
is a national and agency effort

00:07:38.291 --> 00:07:39.959
focused on three core domains:

00:07:40.593 --> 00:07:43.696
lower earth orbit, lunar orbit
and the surface of the moon,

00:07:44.497 --> 00:07:46.866
and Mars and other
deep space objectives.

00:07:49.135 --> 00:07:52.071
The goals of this campaign
are to transition the U.S.

00:07:52.071 --> 00:07:55.141
human spaceflight in lower earth
orbit to commercial operations,

00:07:55.141 --> 00:07:57.376
which supports NASA
and the needs of an emerging

00:07:57.376 --> 00:07:59.345
private sector market,

00:07:59.345 --> 00:08:01.314
extend our long-duration U.S.

00:08:01.314 --> 00:08:03.549
human spaceflight operations
to the lunar vicinity,

00:08:04.851 --> 00:08:07.720
enable long-term robotic
exploration of the moon,

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.456
both scientific and human,
as we move forward,

00:08:10.456 --> 00:08:12.191
in preparation
for further missions

00:08:12.191 --> 00:08:14.193
taking humans to Mars.

00:08:16.062 --> 00:08:17.530
The objectives in there:
first of all,

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:18.464
we'll start with
lower earth orbit.

00:08:18.464 --> 00:08:20.399
Again, as I said, we want
to end direct support

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:22.068
to the ISS by 2025,

00:08:22.068 --> 00:08:24.070
while stimulating
commercial industry

00:08:24.070 --> 00:08:25.938
to develop capabilities.

00:08:25.938 --> 00:08:28.207
NASA and the private
sector can utilize

00:08:28.207 --> 00:08:30.309
and meet NASA's exploration

00:08:30.309 --> 00:08:32.545
risk mitigation and
scientific requirements.

00:08:33.446 --> 00:08:35.915
Starting in 2018 we'll increased
the breadth and depth

00:08:35.915 --> 00:08:37.450
of the commercial

00:08:37.450 --> 00:08:39.418
and international
lower earth activities.

00:08:39.418 --> 00:08:41.287
Specifically,
we'll offer to expand

00:08:41.287 --> 00:08:43.789
the international space station
partnerships to new nations.

00:08:44.824 --> 00:08:48.794
Based on inputs from our current
ISS and commercial stakeholders,

00:08:48.794 --> 00:08:50.663
we'll shape the plan
to transition

00:08:50.663 --> 00:08:52.865
the international space station
as we've been asked to go do.

00:08:53.799 --> 00:08:55.501
We'll extend
the public/private partnerships

00:08:55.501 --> 00:08:57.970
to help develop and demonstrate
the technologies

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:00.940
and capabilities that the new,
commercial products

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:02.909
can be brought to bear
in lower earth orbit.

00:09:04.677 --> 00:09:06.279
At the moon,
we have two objectives.

00:09:06.279 --> 00:09:08.047
Of course,
it's a long-term presence

00:09:08.047 --> 00:09:09.615
in the vicinity of the moon
and on the moon,

00:09:10.249 --> 00:09:11.784
again, both scientifically

00:09:11.784 --> 00:09:12.985
and from a human perspective.

00:09:13.786 --> 00:09:15.354
In the lunar orbit we'll conduct

00:09:15.354 --> 00:09:17.657
the first un-crewed mission
of the SLS Orion,

00:09:18.157 --> 00:09:19.959
first flight in 2020
to the moon,

00:09:19.959 --> 00:09:22.161
and the crewed flight in 2023.

00:09:23.596 --> 00:09:25.398
We intend to establish
a human tended

00:09:25.398 --> 00:09:28.034
lunar orbiting platform
for crews to visit from Earth

00:09:28.034 --> 00:09:30.069
to transit to
and from the lunar surface,

00:09:31.037 --> 00:09:33.506
and to depart to,
ultimately, return to Mars.

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:37.176
We'll develop the lunar orbiting
platform gateway that,

00:09:37.176 --> 00:09:40.513
at a minimum, it puts a power
of propulsion element out there,

00:09:40.513 --> 00:09:42.148
and begins to put the habitat

00:09:42.148 --> 00:09:44.116
that we're going to need
to stay in when we go there.

00:09:45.051 --> 00:09:46.385
At the surface,

00:09:46.385 --> 00:09:48.754
we'll orchestrate
a lunar robotics campaign

00:09:48.754 --> 00:09:52.525
where the folks growing a
commercial base of partnerships

00:09:52.525 --> 00:09:55.962
and activity that can support
U.S. science, technology,

00:09:55.962 --> 00:09:57.596
and exploration objectives,

00:09:57.596 --> 00:09:59.699
and we'll include
international participation,

00:09:59.699 --> 00:10:01.067
where appropriate.

00:10:01.067 --> 00:10:02.902
We'll support a small
commercial lander

00:10:02.902 --> 00:10:05.171
initiative with initial
strategic presence on the moon

00:10:05.171 --> 00:10:07.206
no later than 2020,

00:10:07.206 --> 00:10:09.575
develop a mid to large
scale lander initiative

00:10:09.575 --> 00:10:12.011
working toward human rating
a lander in the future.

00:10:12.578 --> 00:10:14.814
This initiative will focus
on enabling, again,

00:10:14.814 --> 00:10:16.515
commercial and
international partnerships.

00:10:17.083 --> 00:10:19.051
We'll also support an early
science and technology

00:10:19.051 --> 00:10:21.454
initiative that includes
cubesats,

00:10:21.454 --> 00:10:24.323
lunar cubesats, a virtual lunar
institute, and other activities.

00:10:25.391 --> 00:10:26.659
This will further
enable and nurture

00:10:26.659 --> 00:10:29.195
the entrepreneurial
and commercial market forces

00:10:29.195 --> 00:10:31.964
that will define the long-term
human exploration

00:10:31.964 --> 00:10:34.000
and advancement
of the lunar surface.

00:10:35.067 --> 00:10:38.170
For Mars and other deep space
objectives that we have,

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:39.438
we really want
to maintain and grow

00:10:39.438 --> 00:10:41.374
the U.S. leadership at Mars.

00:10:41.374 --> 00:10:42.875
We have a rover
going in 2020,

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:47.113
as a first step to demonstrate
sample return strategy.

00:10:47.613 --> 00:10:49.648
It also is going to
take an experiment

00:10:49.648 --> 00:10:50.916
that is going to tell us
whether we can produce

00:10:50.916 --> 00:10:53.252
oxygen from
the atmosphere on Mars,

00:10:53.252 --> 00:10:55.621
a very exciting
mission for us then.

00:10:55.621 --> 00:10:57.156
We'll use this mission
as a building block

00:10:57.156 --> 00:11:00.192
for subsequent round-trip
robotic missions with,

00:11:00.192 --> 00:11:02.528
hopefully, the first historic
launch off of another planet

00:11:02.528 --> 00:11:05.064
and a sample return
through the lunar gateway

00:11:05.064 --> 00:11:06.298
that we're building;

00:11:06.298 --> 00:11:08.801
again, broadening the
expirational architecture

00:11:08.801 --> 00:11:10.302
as we move forward.

00:11:10.302 --> 00:11:12.738
We'll prioritize these
investments to guide us

00:11:12.738 --> 00:11:15.608
and really align,
as General McMaster said,

00:11:15.608 --> 00:11:17.009
really align toward exploration.

00:11:17.009 --> 00:11:19.412
It's a tremendous focus there
for us as we move forward.

00:11:19.412 --> 00:11:22.615
So, that's kind of the nuance
and the response to SPD1,

00:11:23.482 --> 00:11:26.318
and I think what you'll find,
Mr. Vice President,

00:11:26.318 --> 00:11:28.521
is this NASA team,
your industry team,

00:11:28.521 --> 00:11:29.955
and our international
partners are ready,

00:11:30.456 --> 00:11:31.624
and ready to get started.

00:11:31.624 --> 00:11:33.926
So, thanks for your support
in the 2019 budget.

00:11:33.926 --> 00:11:36.162
We did see the increase,
and we're ready to go do this.

00:11:36.162 --> 00:11:37.163
Thank you.

