Deputy Secretary Rosen: Yes,
thank you Mr. Vice President.

00:12:41.427 --> 00:12:44.130
I'm so pleased to be here
with the Space Council

00:12:44.130 --> 00:12:46.799
and all of us from the
Department of Transportation

00:12:46.799 --> 00:12:48.134
very much appreciate

00:12:48.134 --> 00:12:49.735
and are grateful
for your leadership.

00:12:50.402 --> 00:12:52.505
Secretary Chao was unable
to make it today,

00:12:52.505 --> 00:12:54.773
but she asked that
I make very clear

00:12:54.773 --> 00:12:56.442
that the Department
of Transportation

00:12:56.442 --> 00:12:58.077
is strongly committed

00:12:58.077 --> 00:13:00.012
to regulatory streamlining

00:13:00.012 --> 00:13:03.015
and modernizing our commercial
space regulatory framework.

00:13:04.550 --> 00:13:06.952
As was mentioned at the previous
meeting of the Council,

00:13:06.952 --> 00:13:10.289
you asked us, along with OMB
and the Department of Commerce,

00:13:10.289 --> 00:13:14.193
to prepare a new 45 day plan
to overhaul, modernize,

00:13:14.193 --> 00:13:16.962
and streamline
our somewhat rusty

00:13:16.962 --> 00:13:19.331
commercial space
licensing framework.

00:13:19.331 --> 00:13:20.900
So, we've worked
hard to do that,

00:13:21.534 --> 00:13:23.035
and we've come up
with some structural

00:13:23.035 --> 00:13:25.271
and meaningful changes
to the status quo,

00:13:25.938 --> 00:13:27.106
and I hope the work we did,

00:13:27.106 --> 00:13:28.741
in combination
with our colleagues

00:13:28.741 --> 00:13:30.176
on the Council
and other agencies,

00:13:30.176 --> 00:13:31.644
will meet with your approval.

00:13:31.644 --> 00:13:33.245
There are five main elements

00:13:33.245 --> 00:13:35.014
that I just want to touch
on briefly today.

00:13:36.315 --> 00:13:38.884
The first is we want
to implement

00:13:38.884 --> 00:13:41.287
accelerated rule-making plans,

00:13:41.287 --> 00:13:43.489
meaning that we shorten
the time lines

00:13:43.489 --> 00:13:47.259
that the FAA and the department
are working on

00:13:47.259 --> 00:13:49.662
to meet the ambitious schedule

00:13:49.662 --> 00:13:51.530
that you and the Council
have set out.

00:13:52.431 --> 00:13:57.503
Second, is we want to provide
some immediate interim relief,

00:13:58.204 --> 00:14:00.306
such as the expanded
use of waivers

00:14:00.306 --> 00:14:01.640
and programmatic approvals,

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:03.175
where they're appropriate,

00:14:03.175 --> 00:14:05.344
so that we can try to right away

00:14:05.344 --> 00:14:07.813
begin facilitating the
objectives of the Council.

00:14:08.814 --> 00:14:12.685
A third piece of the plan
is to focus FAA resources

00:14:12.685 --> 00:14:15.688
so that we strengthen
the portion of the FAA

00:14:16.188 --> 00:14:18.591
that most directly
deals with licensing

00:14:19.158 --> 00:14:21.193
and the regulatory approvals

00:14:21.193 --> 00:14:24.296
so that we can accomplish the
goals that have been set out.

00:14:25.297 --> 00:14:29.768
A fourth item is to establish
a joint task force.

00:14:30.302 --> 00:14:33.505
The purpose of this is to
facilitate better coordination

00:14:33.505 --> 00:14:35.241
within the U.S. government

00:14:35.241 --> 00:14:38.611
so that people that need
regulatory approvals

00:14:39.111 --> 00:14:42.314
don't face confusing situations
as to who's doing what

00:14:42.314 --> 00:14:44.383
and how to get
the approvals they need.

00:14:45.217 --> 00:14:48.754
But then the fifth piece,
and perhaps the most important,

00:14:48.754 --> 00:14:51.056
is a new licensing framework.

00:14:51.056 --> 00:14:53.926
As was set out in recommendation
one for today's meeting,

00:14:54.493 --> 00:14:58.831
our ultimate aim
is a 21st-century file

00:14:58.831 --> 00:15:01.367
and fly kind of
licensing framework,

00:15:01.867 --> 00:15:05.704
and the plan includes specific
new regulatory deadlines

00:15:05.704 --> 00:15:08.907
and approaches in the aim
of getting us to a file

00:15:08.907 --> 00:15:12.811
and fly type regulatory approach
as quickly as possible.

00:15:13.712 --> 00:15:15.314
So, we look forward
to implementing

00:15:15.314 --> 00:15:16.982
this changed approach

00:15:16.982 --> 00:15:18.984
and delivering
on a more responsive,

00:15:18.984 --> 00:15:22.154
easier to navigate
and sensible commercial space

00:15:22.154 --> 00:15:23.822
regulatory framework,

00:15:23.822 --> 00:15:25.291
and very much look forward

00:15:25.291 --> 00:15:28.661
to working with all the folks
on this Council

00:15:28.661 --> 00:15:30.162
and others
to make that happen.

00:15:30.696 --> 00:15:32.665
Thank you.

00:15:32.665 --> 00:15:41.407
(Applause.)

00:15:41.407 --> 00:15:43.008
The Vice President:
Thank you, Jeffrey,

00:15:43.008 --> 00:15:46.712
and with that, let me recognize
the Secretary of Commerce,

00:15:47.713 --> 00:15:49.481
Wilbur Ross, who I know
has been working

00:15:49.481 --> 00:15:50.916
very closely with Secretary Chao

00:15:50.916 --> 00:15:54.753
to achieve exactly the
streamlining, the objectives,

00:15:54.753 --> 00:15:56.355
and the re-organization
that we've discussed.

00:15:56.355 --> 00:15:57.723
Mr. Secretary, thank you.

00:15:57.723 --> 00:15:59.224
Secretary Ross:
Thank you Mr. Vice President.

00:16:00.993 --> 00:16:05.130
Mr. Vice President, members of
the National Space Council,

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:08.300
users advisory group,
and distinguished guests,

00:16:09.201 --> 00:16:11.637
recently here
at Cape Canaveral,

00:16:11.637 --> 00:16:15.441
SpaceX's Falcon heavy
rocket was launched.

00:16:16.008 --> 00:16:19.511
Two first stage boosters
disengaged on schedule

00:16:20.045 --> 00:16:22.348
and landed back here.

00:16:23.215 --> 00:16:24.883
This was their second use.

00:16:25.484 --> 00:16:28.020
You saw one of them
as you came in.

00:16:28.954 --> 00:16:32.157
It will be ready
for its third launch,

00:16:32.157 --> 00:16:35.994
an amazing technological
and commercial feat.

00:16:36.995 --> 00:16:40.432
Thanks to impressive
events such as this,

00:16:40.966 --> 00:16:44.870
the United States is the leader
in space once again.

00:16:45.571 --> 00:16:47.773
Somewhere out there in space,

00:16:47.773 --> 00:16:49.475
there is a bright red roadster

00:16:49.975 --> 00:16:52.344
going thousands
of miles per hour,

00:16:52.878 --> 00:16:54.713
the fastest car in history.

00:16:54.713 --> 00:16:55.514
(Laughter.)

00:16:55.514 --> 00:16:57.216
We had better keep up with it.

00:16:57.216 --> 00:16:58.884
(Laughter.)

00:16:58.884 --> 00:17:04.022
Space is already a
$330 billion industry,

00:17:04.022 --> 00:17:08.293
supporting 211,000
American jobs.

00:17:08.894 --> 00:17:14.366
But our share of
the 1,700 new companies

00:17:14.366 --> 00:17:17.169
created worldwide last year

00:17:17.169 --> 00:17:19.138
was only 45 percent,

00:17:19.671 --> 00:17:23.041
far lower than
our share of launches.

00:17:23.809 --> 00:17:27.546
Private companies
funded $3.9 billion

00:17:28.247 --> 00:17:30.582
of our space effort last year,

00:17:31.183 --> 00:17:35.621
but they're competing against
70 foreign governments.

00:17:35.621 --> 00:17:38.490
So, they need all the support
we can give them.

00:17:39.658 --> 00:17:43.328
Countries new to space
have an inherent advantage

00:17:43.328 --> 00:17:46.965
in terms of the
regulatory environment

00:17:46.965 --> 00:17:51.036
because they carry no baggage
from the earlier,

00:17:51.036 --> 00:17:55.474
simpler days of space.
In contrast,

00:17:55.474 --> 00:17:59.578
much of our remote
sensing regulatory regime

00:17:59.578 --> 00:18:01.547
is 25 years old.

00:18:02.214 --> 00:18:08.587
Space 25 years ago bears little
resemblance to space today.

00:18:09.555 --> 00:18:12.391
Now the rate of innovation
is extraordinary.

00:18:12.925 --> 00:18:14.493
So, we need an adaptive

00:18:14.993 --> 00:18:18.831
and relatively permissive
regulatory system.

00:18:19.665 --> 00:18:25.771
NOAA, FAA, FCC, and other
agencies each have a role,

00:18:26.405 --> 00:18:30.509
and they all have
obligations to DOD,

00:18:30.509 --> 00:18:33.479
the IC and the state as well.

00:18:34.146 --> 00:18:37.583
That complexity
inherently causes delay.

00:18:38.617 --> 00:18:41.854
Since the Council's first
meeting in October,

00:18:42.588 --> 00:18:46.525
Commerce's review of the
outdated regulatory framework

00:18:47.125 --> 00:18:50.295
and discussions
with an ambitious,

00:18:50.295 --> 00:18:52.664
but frustrated space industry,

00:18:53.232 --> 00:18:57.736
made it clear that the rate
of regulatory change

00:18:57.736 --> 00:19:01.240
must match the rate
of technological change.

00:19:02.808 --> 00:19:04.610
That is how we will ensure

00:19:05.377 --> 00:19:08.881
that businesses choose
the United States

00:19:08.881 --> 00:19:11.817
as their flag
of choice for space.

00:19:12.618 --> 00:19:16.822
So, at the department,
we're working to create a new,

00:19:16.822 --> 00:19:20.392
one-stop shop
for space commerce.

00:19:21.126 --> 00:19:24.596
Mr. Vice President,
with the Council's direction,

00:19:24.596 --> 00:19:27.833
I will move the Office
of Space Commerce

00:19:27.833 --> 00:19:31.370
and the Commercial Remote
Sensing Regulatory Affairs

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:35.741
Office from NOAA
to my direct oversight

00:19:35.741 --> 00:19:37.676
in the Office
of the Secretary.

00:19:37.676 --> 00:19:46.685
(Applause.)

00:19:46.685 --> 00:19:51.490
This elevated and amplified
Office of Space Commerce

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:53.926
will coordinate all space

00:19:53.926 --> 00:19:55.294
related functions

00:19:55.294 --> 00:19:56.962
at the department;

00:19:56.962 --> 00:20:00.065
remote sensing,
spectrum policy,

00:20:00.999 --> 00:20:05.103
export controls, business
and trade promotion,

00:20:05.103 --> 00:20:07.239
to name a few.

00:20:07.239 --> 00:20:09.875
In addition to
the proposed relocation

00:20:09.875 --> 00:20:11.910
of the Office of Space Commerce,

00:20:12.544 --> 00:20:16.248
we will also soon name
a director of that office.

00:20:17.316 --> 00:20:22.354
Also, we are providing to the
Bureau of Industry and Security

00:20:22.354 --> 00:20:25.991
and the NTIA additional funding

00:20:25.991 --> 00:20:29.094
for their space
focused activities,

00:20:29.728 --> 00:20:32.798
and our foreign
commercial service teams

00:20:32.798 --> 00:20:36.034
located in 105 cities
around the world

00:20:36.602 --> 00:20:41.273
will recruit foreign space
businesses to our country.

00:20:42.307 --> 00:20:46.979
Space will be featured during a
select USA conference in June,

00:20:47.512 --> 00:20:52.217
which last year attracted
3,000 foreign participants.

00:20:53.018 --> 00:20:56.955
The department further proposes
to the Space Council

00:20:56.955 --> 00:21:00.826
that all space commerce
responsibilities

00:21:00.826 --> 00:21:04.896
other than launch
and reentry licensing

00:21:04.896 --> 00:21:06.632
be consolidated

00:21:06.632 --> 00:21:08.700
into the Department
of Commerce.

00:21:09.735 --> 00:21:12.337
We further recommend
that the President

00:21:12.337 --> 00:21:15.107
direct the Office
of Space Commerce

00:21:15.107 --> 00:21:18.176
to develop in concert
with the Council

00:21:18.176 --> 00:21:22.848
and industry players
regulations and legislation

00:21:22.848 --> 00:21:27.185
for an effective mission
authorization framework

00:21:27.185 --> 00:21:30.756
for all commercial
activities in space.

00:21:32.057 --> 00:21:36.361
We pledge to make those
proposals no later than July 1.

00:21:37.596 --> 00:21:41.767
Activities such as asteroid
mining, space tourism,

00:21:41.767 --> 00:21:45.437
and space habitation
are quickly becoming

00:21:45.437 --> 00:21:47.539
much more than
science fiction,

00:21:48.206 --> 00:21:52.644
and we need a future-oriented
space commerce agenda

00:21:52.644 --> 00:21:55.013
and a supportive
regulatory regime.

00:21:55.714 --> 00:21:58.717
With input and guidance
from the Space Council,

00:21:59.251 --> 00:22:00.585
the Department of Commerce

00:22:00.585 --> 00:22:05.791
can be the one-stop shop
the industry so sorely needs.

00:22:07.926 --> 00:22:10.762
In addition, the department
recommends

00:22:10.762 --> 00:22:13.265
that the Departments
of Commerce, State,

00:22:13.265 --> 00:22:18.370
and Defense continue their
efforts to simplify existing

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:22.207
commercial remote
sensing licensing regimes.

00:22:22.808 --> 00:22:26.845
That process must be made
more efficient and predictable.

00:22:27.612 --> 00:22:32.150
Satellite companies now face
a permitting timeline

00:22:32.150 --> 00:22:37.189
that can take five years,
is undefined, indefinite,

00:22:37.189 --> 00:22:41.660
and provides no certainty
or predictability to industry.

00:22:42.728 --> 00:22:46.098
This is unacceptable,
and must change.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:52.137
Otherwise, companies and
customers will go overseas.

00:22:52.738 --> 00:22:54.372
There are at least
two other areas

00:22:54.372 --> 00:22:57.375
where Commerce can play
an important role

00:22:57.375 --> 00:22:59.578
for American
leadership in space.

00:23:00.212 --> 00:23:04.082
These are in spectrum policy
and export licensing.

00:23:04.649 --> 00:23:08.653
Spectrum is a scarce resource

00:23:08.653 --> 00:23:12.124
that facilitates
communications control

00:23:12.124 --> 00:23:15.627
and transmission of
valuable data back to Earth.

00:23:16.728 --> 00:23:19.731
The National Space Council
should recommend

00:23:19.731 --> 00:23:22.501
that the department
be directed to develop

00:23:22.501 --> 00:23:26.037
and advocate
for spectrum policies

00:23:26.037 --> 00:23:29.474
to support commercial
space activities,

00:23:29.474 --> 00:23:32.778
while respecting the needs
of DOD and others.

00:23:33.411 --> 00:23:37.616
Finally, Commerce recommends
that the Space Council

00:23:37.616 --> 00:23:41.286
and the executive
secretary review export

00:23:41.286 --> 00:23:43.555
licensing regulations

00:23:43.555 --> 00:23:46.291
affecting commercial
space activity.

00:23:47.459 --> 00:23:52.430
Today, a space vehicle
that returns to earth

00:23:52.430 --> 00:23:57.135
in international waters
or non-U.S. territory

00:23:57.135 --> 00:23:59.704
is treated as an export

00:23:59.704 --> 00:24:02.407
of sensitive
and dangerous technology.

00:24:03.141 --> 00:24:08.180
This approach is a primary
complaint of space companies,

00:24:08.814 --> 00:24:12.317
and if the President approves
our recommendations,

00:24:12.317 --> 00:24:16.855
we will continue working with
our colleagues at State and DOD

00:24:16.855 --> 00:24:19.224
to enable more
commercial activity,

00:24:19.724 --> 00:24:21.893
while protecting
national security.

00:24:22.894 --> 00:24:26.464
That little red Tesla
in outer space

00:24:26.464 --> 00:24:28.433
does need rules of the road,

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:32.871
but there shouldn't be
too many one-way streets,

00:24:32.871 --> 00:24:35.307
dead ends, or u-turns.

00:24:35.307 --> 00:24:38.376
I promise you, Commerce
will be a good steward.

00:24:39.644 --> 00:24:41.613
Thank you.

00:24:41.613 --> 00:24:48.954
(Applause.)

00:24:48.954 --> 00:24:50.455
The Vice President:
Well, thank you Wilbur.

00:24:50.455 --> 00:24:52.357
Thank you for your great work

00:24:52.357 --> 00:24:55.460
and the department's
great work in this area

00:24:55.460 --> 00:24:59.064
will speak to your
recommendations momentarily.

00:24:59.064 --> 00:25:04.135
But, I think everyone looking on
can tell the great collaboration

00:25:04.135 --> 00:25:06.638
between the Department
of Commerce

00:25:06.638 --> 00:25:07.939
and the Department
of Transportation,

00:25:08.807 --> 00:25:10.508
and appreciate
so very much the work done.

00:25:11.476 --> 00:25:15.413
We'll turn our attention
now to Administrator Rao.

00:25:17.015 --> 00:25:18.650
Thank you for being here today.

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:21.286
Most people may not be aware
of how important your job

00:25:21.286 --> 00:25:26.458
is to this industry at the
Office of Management and Budget.

00:25:26.458 --> 00:25:28.059
You lead the Office
of Information

00:25:28.059 --> 00:25:29.327
and Regulatory Affairs.

00:25:29.327 --> 00:25:30.996
It's critical to the work
of this Council.

00:25:30.996 --> 00:25:32.530
I want to thank
Director Mulvaney,

00:25:33.798 --> 00:25:36.768
who has been working tirelessly
to move the President's agenda,

00:25:36.768 --> 00:25:38.603
and streamlining
regulatory regimes.

00:25:38.603 --> 00:25:41.239
Could you give us
a quick overview

00:25:41.239 --> 00:25:43.541
of what you have
been working for,

00:25:44.042 --> 00:25:46.678
working toward in the office
to support this effort?

00:25:46.678 --> 00:25:49.014
Administrator Rao:
Sure, thank you

00:25:49.014 --> 00:25:50.348
very much, Mr. Vice President.

00:25:50.348 --> 00:25:52.417
It's a pleasure to be here
with members of the Cabinet,

00:25:52.417 --> 00:25:54.819
the Space Council,
and other distinguished guests

00:25:54.819 --> 00:25:57.222
for this very exciting
and ambitious event.

00:25:58.223 --> 00:26:01.226
So, as you mentioned,
I'm the administrator at OIRA,

00:26:01.226 --> 00:26:03.094
which is the office that reviews

00:26:03.094 --> 00:26:04.796
all the significant regulatory

00:26:04.796 --> 00:26:06.298
actions across the government.

00:26:06.998 --> 00:26:08.767
And in a nutshell,
what we really do

00:26:08.767 --> 00:26:10.669
is we try to ensure
that regulations

00:26:10.669 --> 00:26:12.003
serve the American people.

00:26:12.804 --> 00:26:15.173
And since the Reagan
administration,

00:26:15.173 --> 00:26:18.043
we help agencies meet
presidential priorities

00:26:18.043 --> 00:26:20.312
such as what we're
talking about today;

00:26:20.312 --> 00:26:23.348
the commitment to winning
the next frontier of space.

00:26:24.616 --> 00:26:26.418
So, Mr. Vice President,
as you've already said

00:26:26.418 --> 00:26:29.788
so well there are tremendous
opportunities here to use space

00:26:29.788 --> 00:26:32.157
for security
and commercial purposes.

00:26:33.024 --> 00:26:34.926
But the success of these
ambitious ventures

00:26:34.926 --> 00:26:37.262
will depend in part
on a regulatory system

00:26:37.262 --> 00:26:39.764
that does not stand
in the way of progress

00:26:39.764 --> 00:26:42.834
but, instead, enables
innovation, provides clarity,

00:26:42.834 --> 00:26:45.270
and ensures safety.

00:26:45.270 --> 00:26:47.572
These goals with respect
to space development

00:26:47.572 --> 00:26:50.709
are consistent with President
Trump's overall direction

00:26:50.709 --> 00:26:53.511
to reduce cumulative
regulatory burdens

00:26:53.511 --> 00:26:55.213
across the government.

00:26:55.213 --> 00:26:58.049
As an administration, we want
to advance a regulatory --

00:26:58.049 --> 00:27:01.886
(audio break)

00:27:01.886 --> 00:27:04.289
and that leaves
individuals and businesses

00:27:04.289 --> 00:27:06.624
as free as possible to innovate

00:27:06.624 --> 00:27:09.027
and to create the
technology of the future.

00:27:10.528 --> 00:27:12.797
These general principles
apply across the board,

00:27:12.797 --> 00:27:14.632
but really have
particular importance

00:27:14.632 --> 00:27:16.368
in areas of
emerging technology,

00:27:16.368 --> 00:27:17.869
such as space exploration.

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:20.939
And here we start
with the basic idea

00:27:20.939 --> 00:27:22.807
that government shouldn't
be picking winners

00:27:22.807 --> 00:27:24.576
and losers through regulation.

00:27:25.610 --> 00:27:27.045
We don't want
to regulate in a way

00:27:27.045 --> 00:27:29.514
that freezes
technological development

00:27:29.514 --> 00:27:32.217
or stifles innovation through
government prescriptions.

00:27:33.151 --> 00:27:35.987
And as Secretary Ross
and Deputy Secretary Rosen

00:27:35.987 --> 00:27:38.690
have already mentioned,
important reform begins

00:27:38.690 --> 00:27:41.059
first by identifying
some of the problems

00:27:41.059 --> 00:27:43.294
with existing
regulatory frameworks.

00:27:44.496 --> 00:27:46.398
We need to find those
regulations that are

00:27:46.398 --> 00:27:48.133
duplicative, outdated,

00:27:48.133 --> 00:27:50.035
or just simply ineffective

00:27:50.035 --> 00:27:53.338
and then work hard to eliminate
or streamline those burdens.

00:27:54.672 --> 00:27:57.042
And in areas where
multiple agencies impose

00:27:57.042 --> 00:27:58.443
overlapping burdens

00:27:58.443 --> 00:28:01.513
such as in licensing
or paperwork reporting,

00:28:01.513 --> 00:28:03.848
we are reconsidering
how those requirements

00:28:03.848 --> 00:28:05.683
can be combined or replaced.

00:28:06.284 --> 00:28:09.487
And in part because of because
of our centralized role at OIRA,

00:28:09.487 --> 00:28:12.290
we can address issues
that span multiple agencies

00:28:13.258 --> 00:28:16.795
to eliminate and streamline
unnecessary requirements.

00:28:17.595 --> 00:28:19.831
And that simply will
allow more resources

00:28:19.831 --> 00:28:22.534
to be devoted to
research and production,

00:28:22.534 --> 00:28:24.469
rather than regulatory red tape.

00:28:26.137 --> 00:28:28.573
And we're confident that we can
do this for space development

00:28:28.573 --> 00:28:30.842
because we've done this
in other regulatory areas.

00:28:31.376 --> 00:28:34.612
The President has demonstrated

00:28:34.612 --> 00:28:36.581
tremendous leadership
in this area,

00:28:36.581 --> 00:28:39.017
and directed significant
and meaningful regulatory

00:28:39.017 --> 00:28:41.753
reform since the outset
of the administration.

00:28:42.754 --> 00:28:45.056
His early executive order
called for eliminating

00:28:45.056 --> 00:28:46.991
two regulations
for each new one,

00:28:47.826 --> 00:28:49.160
and as of the last
fiscal year,

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:52.263
we were actually at
22 deregulatory actions

00:28:52.263 --> 00:28:53.665
for each new one.

00:28:53.665 --> 00:28:55.834
And in this coming year
agencies have proposed

00:28:55.834 --> 00:28:57.735
even more deregulatory actions

00:28:57.735 --> 00:28:59.204
and projecting a regulatory

00:28:59.204 --> 00:29:01.206
cost savings of
over $10 billion.

00:29:03.141 --> 00:29:04.976
So, in the past,
regulatory burdens

00:29:04.976 --> 00:29:06.811
have steadily
increased over time.

00:29:07.412 --> 00:29:09.914
But this administration
has really turned the tide

00:29:09.914 --> 00:29:12.183
with its regulatory
reform initiatives.

00:29:13.151 --> 00:29:16.721
And so, in areas
of burgeoning technology

00:29:16.721 --> 00:29:18.423
such as space development,

00:29:18.423 --> 00:29:20.358
this means individuals
and companies

00:29:20.358 --> 00:29:21.860
can proceed with confidence

00:29:21.860 --> 00:29:25.029
that we're not going to spring
new regulatory requirements

00:29:25.029 --> 00:29:26.531
on them that will stifle growth.

00:29:27.398 --> 00:29:29.934
We want to contribute
to a regulatory environment

00:29:29.934 --> 00:29:31.736
that can enhance
development of space,

00:29:32.670 --> 00:29:35.006
and with the right
frameworks we're confident

00:29:35.006 --> 00:29:36.741
that private companies
can unleash

00:29:36.741 --> 00:29:38.276
creativity and ingenuity.

00:29:39.144 --> 00:29:41.813
And we can enhance
American global leadership

00:29:41.813 --> 00:29:44.048
by attracting
investments in research

00:29:44.048 --> 00:29:45.517
and development for space.

00:29:45.517 --> 00:29:48.786
Of course, with further
advances into space,

00:29:48.786 --> 00:29:51.189
we face important
questions about security,

00:29:51.189 --> 00:29:52.757
safety, sovereignty.

00:29:53.391 --> 00:29:55.360
But, with the work
of the Space Council,

00:29:55.360 --> 00:29:58.763
OIRA remains committed
to working across the government

00:29:58.763 --> 00:30:01.933
to design regulations
that meet these needs,

00:30:01.933 --> 00:30:04.736
while furthering our journey
to the next frontiers of space.

00:30:05.403 --> 00:30:07.405
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

00:30:08.673 --> 00:30:09.240
The Vice President:
Thank you, Neomi.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:10.909
(Applause.)

00:30:10.909 --> 00:30:15.113
Well done. Okay.

00:30:15.113 --> 00:30:17.282
This -- we're approaching
the end

00:30:17.282 --> 00:30:19.150
