00:38:33.277 --> 00:38:34.545
Mr. Cheng: Good morning,
Mr. Vice President,

00:38:34.545 --> 00:38:36.247
members of the Space Council,

00:38:36.247 --> 00:38:38.382
the National Space Council.
My name is Dean Cheng.

00:38:38.382 --> 00:38:41.018
The views I express
in this testimony are my own;

00:38:41.018 --> 00:38:43.387
they should not be construed as
reflecting the official position

00:38:43.387 --> 00:38:45.056
of the Heritage Foundation.

00:38:45.056 --> 00:38:47.692
During the Cold War, there were
only two major space powers,

00:38:47.692 --> 00:38:49.660
the United States
and the Soviet Union,

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:51.696
and they had roughly
symmetric interests

00:38:51.696 --> 00:38:52.930
and approaches to space.

00:38:53.497 --> 00:38:54.965
Like so much of
international security,

00:38:54.965 --> 00:38:57.835
the post-Cold War world
is much more complex.

00:38:57.835 --> 00:38:59.603
There are more
space players today,

00:38:59.603 --> 00:39:02.873
including a growing set of
non-state and commercial actors.

00:39:03.507 --> 00:39:05.376
At the same,
the American dependence

00:39:05.376 --> 00:39:06.644
on space has broadened.

00:39:06.644 --> 00:39:09.980
The U.S. military depends
upon space-based systems

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:11.215
for the American
way of war.

00:39:11.782 --> 00:39:13.584
Financial institutions, farmers,

00:39:13.584 --> 00:39:16.754
and Amazon all increasingly
depend on space systems

00:39:16.754 --> 00:39:18.656
for their day-to-day operations.

00:39:18.656 --> 00:39:20.157
Given this dependence,

00:39:20.157 --> 00:39:23.194
revisionist powers
and security competitors

00:39:23.194 --> 00:39:25.963
are likely to target
American space systems

00:39:25.963 --> 00:39:28.933
as an essential means
of countering American economic

00:39:28.933 --> 00:39:30.301
and military capability.

00:39:31.068 --> 00:39:32.837
This evolving set
of circumstances

00:39:32.837 --> 00:39:35.005
for both space
and American security

00:39:35.005 --> 00:39:36.974
is reflected in
the growing challenge

00:39:36.974 --> 00:39:38.776
posed by the other space powers,

00:39:38.776 --> 00:39:40.711
and especially the People's
Republic of China.

00:39:41.645 --> 00:39:43.814
The PRC has pursued
a set of space policies

00:39:43.814 --> 00:39:48.452
that do not parallel
American or Soviet ones,

00:39:48.452 --> 00:39:51.655
and it is now exploiting
not only new technologies

00:39:51.655 --> 00:39:53.724
to expand
its space capabilities,

00:39:53.724 --> 00:39:57.328
but also taking new
organizational approaches

00:39:57.328 --> 00:39:58.763
and innovations.

00:39:58.763 --> 00:40:01.398
Some of the key characteristics
of the Chinese space challenge

00:40:01.398 --> 00:40:03.033
include, first and foremost,

00:40:03.033 --> 00:40:06.837
that China is fundamentally
a major space power.

00:40:06.837 --> 00:40:08.773
China possesses all of
the key elements

00:40:08.773 --> 00:40:11.509
required for supporting
a major space presence.

00:40:11.509 --> 00:40:14.278
Above all, it has the political
will to support

00:40:14.278 --> 00:40:17.014
and sustain national
commitments to space.

00:40:17.581 --> 00:40:20.284
China has also committed
the industrial, financial,

00:40:20.284 --> 00:40:23.521
and human capital
to translate those desires

00:40:23.521 --> 00:40:26.423
into today's array
of satellites, boosters,

00:40:26.423 --> 00:40:28.159
and launch sites,

00:40:28.159 --> 00:40:30.494
and it is important to note
that those systems

00:40:30.494 --> 00:40:33.697
are largely indigenously
designed and constructed.

00:40:34.198 --> 00:40:37.601
China may engage in all sorts
of industrial espionage,

00:40:37.601 --> 00:40:41.305
but much of its space program
is indigenous and homegrown.

00:40:42.206 --> 00:40:45.042
China's space program has
a very heavy military component.

00:40:45.609 --> 00:40:47.011
The basic reality is that

00:40:47.011 --> 00:40:49.113
when we interact with
China's space program,

00:40:49.113 --> 00:40:52.082
we are essentially interacting
with China's military.

00:40:52.683 --> 00:40:54.718
China's space
facilities, personnel,

00:40:54.718 --> 00:40:57.688
and programs are largely drawn
from that military.

00:40:57.688 --> 00:41:02.393
Its facilities are PLA bases,
their staffs are PLA personnel,

00:41:02.393 --> 00:41:03.694
and the heads of key programs,

00:41:03.694 --> 00:41:06.797
such as the China Manned
Space Engineering Office,

00:41:06.797 --> 00:41:08.499
are drawn from the military.

00:41:09.333 --> 00:41:10.668
China's space program, however,

00:41:10.668 --> 00:41:13.103
also reflects
its approach of dual-use

00:41:13.103 --> 00:41:14.805
as civil/military integration.

00:41:15.306 --> 00:41:19.143
China's space industrial complex
is not so much a revolving door

00:41:19.143 --> 00:41:22.580
as a broad atrium for Chinese
air and space engineers

00:41:22.580 --> 00:41:26.083
and managers amidst all of these
state-owned enterprises.

00:41:26.083 --> 00:41:29.887
And the result is far closer
to a single integrated space

00:41:29.887 --> 00:41:32.923
enterprise with relatively
few demarcations

00:41:32.923 --> 00:41:34.658
between the military
and civilian.

00:41:35.526 --> 00:41:37.928
This reality will likely
apply to China's

00:41:37.928 --> 00:41:41.365
emerging set of commercial
space entities as well.

00:41:41.365 --> 00:41:43.734
China is actually
promoting the development

00:41:43.734 --> 00:41:45.970
of new commercial
space companies

00:41:45.970 --> 00:41:48.839
that range from those supported
by state-owned enterprises

00:41:48.839 --> 00:41:50.708
to more independent
private firms.

00:41:51.275 --> 00:41:53.677
But given the interest
in melding civilian

00:41:53.677 --> 00:41:55.646
and military capacity,

00:41:55.646 --> 00:41:59.250
as well as past evidence
behavior in the telecomm sector,

00:41:59.250 --> 00:42:02.920
it is vital to recognize
that these private firms will,

00:42:02.920 --> 00:42:05.422
at the end of the day,
respond with alacrity

00:42:05.422 --> 00:42:06.991
to central government
directives.

00:42:07.558 --> 00:42:10.761
The Chinese model will not
be Teslas in space,

00:42:10.761 --> 00:42:12.529
but Huawei in space.

00:42:13.297 --> 00:42:16.000
In conclusion, as the
United States advances space

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.035
as a priority domain,

00:42:18.035 --> 00:42:20.938
it needs to recognize that other
states will not only set --

00:42:20.938 --> 00:42:23.440
seek to do the same
for themselves,

00:42:23.440 --> 00:42:25.943
but some are also
very likely to strive

00:42:26.510 --> 00:42:30.314
to deny space to the
United States in time of crisis,

00:42:30.314 --> 00:42:31.649
and certainly in time of war.

00:42:32.182 --> 00:42:33.651
These efforts
will likely encompass

00:42:33.651 --> 00:42:35.686
not only direct military action

00:42:35.686 --> 00:42:39.023
but efforts at establishing
a highly competitive space

00:42:39.023 --> 00:42:40.291
industrial base

00:42:40.291 --> 00:42:42.626
supporting space-oriented
technologies,

00:42:42.626 --> 00:42:45.195
production,
and organizational innovation,

00:42:45.195 --> 00:42:47.097
and undertaking
an array of efforts

00:42:47.097 --> 00:42:49.166
to access American technologies

00:42:49.166 --> 00:42:51.268
while denying the
United States the same.

00:42:51.268 --> 00:42:52.870
Thank you very much
for the opportunity to testify

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:53.704
before you this morning.

00:42:53.704 --> 00:42:54.838
(Applause.)

00:42:54.838 --> 00:42:56.840
The Vice President:
Thank you, Mr. Cheng.

00:43:00.377 --> 00:43:03.013
Jeffery Manber, with
NanoRocks Corporation;

00:43:03.013 --> 00:43:04.515
thank you for being here.
You're recognized.

00:43:04.515 --> 00:43:05.783
Mr. Manber:
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

00:43:06.283 --> 00:43:08.986
Now, for 30 years --
good morning, everyone.

00:43:08.986 --> 00:43:11.455
For 30 years,
I've worked to make space

00:43:11.455 --> 00:43:13.657
just another place
to do business.

00:43:14.158 --> 00:43:17.761
My inspiration, in large part,
derives from having worked

00:43:17.761 --> 00:43:21.098
under Ronald Reagan's Commerce
Secretary Malcolm Baldridge

00:43:21.098 --> 00:43:23.167
in the original Office
of Space Commerce,

00:43:23.167 --> 00:43:24.768
so it's good to be here
this morning.

00:43:25.602 --> 00:43:28.205
I started my company,
NanoRocks, eight years ago.

00:43:28.806 --> 00:43:31.141
We were the first company
to own and market

00:43:31.141 --> 00:43:32.676
our own research services

00:43:32.676 --> 00:43:34.144
on board the space station.

00:43:34.845 --> 00:43:37.982
We were the first company
to commercially deploy small

00:43:37.982 --> 00:43:39.717
(inaudible)
the space station.

00:43:39.717 --> 00:43:43.153
As of today, we have
launched over 600 payloads

00:43:43.153 --> 00:43:45.556
from customers
in over 30 countries.

00:43:46.223 --> 00:43:48.092
Our commercial customers range

00:43:48.092 --> 00:43:50.928
from the U.S. government
to high schools.

00:43:51.528 --> 00:43:54.531
The U.S. government is
a commercial customer;

00:43:54.531 --> 00:43:57.234
so, too, the high schools,
some of whom do bake sales

00:43:57.234 --> 00:43:59.269
to support the payloads
that go to station.

00:43:59.870 --> 00:44:02.439
And I'm proud to say,
Mr. Vice President,

00:44:02.439 --> 00:44:04.808
that we've launched four
high school experiments

00:44:04.808 --> 00:44:07.211
from Crown Point
and Highland, Indiana.

00:44:08.145 --> 00:44:11.515
So, please allow me several
observations this morning.

00:44:11.515 --> 00:44:13.484
First, kudos to
the administration

00:44:13.484 --> 00:44:16.220
and the council beginning
the debate today

00:44:16.220 --> 00:44:19.723
on the transition from the ISS,

00:44:19.723 --> 00:44:21.692
from a government-owned
facility,

00:44:21.692 --> 00:44:24.094
to an era of private
space stations.

00:44:25.029 --> 00:44:27.998
The debate may have been
skewed a bit in the headlines,

00:44:28.899 --> 00:44:31.635
but I believe you are raising
the correct questions.

00:44:32.436 --> 00:44:40.177
How can NASA most effectively
leverage the taxpayer

00:44:40.177 --> 00:44:41.912
investment in ISS?

00:44:42.780 --> 00:44:45.582
Can commercial industry safely

00:44:45.582 --> 00:44:48.452
and cost effectively
operate the ISS

00:44:48.452 --> 00:44:50.454
in other commercial platforms?

00:44:51.021 --> 00:44:53.624
And we understand,
it's not black and white,

00:44:54.425 --> 00:44:56.894
but it is an end to accepting

00:44:56.894 --> 00:44:59.163
that the government
support of ISS

00:44:59.163 --> 00:45:01.031
is the only pathway,

00:45:01.031 --> 00:45:02.900
and how will the government,
in the future,

00:45:02.900 --> 00:45:05.335
behave more and more
as a tenant,

00:45:05.335 --> 00:45:07.738
just the way it is
in every other marketplace?

00:45:07.738 --> 00:45:09.506
So, we're very excited by this.

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:13.911
Finally, as I look overseas,
it's my opinion,

00:45:13.911 --> 00:45:17.247
as a businessman,
as a space businessman,

00:45:17.247 --> 00:45:20.084
that the United States
cannot simply ignore

00:45:20.084 --> 00:45:22.986
China's commercial
space ambitions.

00:45:22.986 --> 00:45:25.389
Commercial space ambitions.

00:45:25.389 --> 00:45:27.524
China is quietly developing

00:45:27.524 --> 00:45:29.827
a robust commercial
space industry.

00:45:30.427 --> 00:45:33.964
I say "quietly" because
Americans are barred,

00:45:33.964 --> 00:45:37.734
by our own regulations,
and our own mindset,

00:45:37.734 --> 00:45:40.337
from participation
in this marketplace.

00:45:40.938 --> 00:45:43.307
As we just heard,
large Chinese companies

00:45:43.307 --> 00:45:45.309
are creating commercial
launch efforts,

00:45:45.876 --> 00:45:48.745
while young Chinese
entrepreneurs are raising funds

00:45:48.745 --> 00:45:50.547
from Silicon Valley

00:45:50.547 --> 00:45:52.850
on commercial
space projects.

00:45:52.850 --> 00:45:56.253
On a governmental level,
our allies have noticed.

00:45:56.253 --> 00:45:59.156
The European Space Agency
has astronauts training

00:45:59.156 --> 00:46:01.325
to visit the planned
Chinese space station.

00:46:01.825 --> 00:46:05.496
But the U.S. has barred itself
from participation.

00:46:06.563 --> 00:46:08.532
NanoRocks and other companies

00:46:08.532 --> 00:46:11.268
are prohibited to sell
into this marketplace.

00:46:11.835 --> 00:46:14.338
Avoiding this
emerging marketplace,

00:46:14.338 --> 00:46:19.009
albeit to justified concerns
over technology transfer

00:46:19.009 --> 00:46:21.178
and other legitimate issues,

00:46:21.178 --> 00:46:23.614
is not the American
global leadership

00:46:23.614 --> 00:46:25.349
that we all strive to achieve.

00:46:26.350 --> 00:46:28.752
Now, while my time
today is brief,

00:46:28.752 --> 00:46:33.891
I urge us to negotiate a stern
but fair agreement with China

00:46:33.891 --> 00:46:37.294
and allow U.S. businesses
to do what we do best,

00:46:37.294 --> 00:46:40.364
and that is to innovate and
compete better than anyone else.

00:46:41.031 --> 00:46:43.767
Mr. Vice President,
and members of the council,

00:46:44.301 --> 00:46:46.270
I am thrilled that
the administration

00:46:46.270 --> 00:46:48.305
is focusing on commercial space,

00:46:48.305 --> 00:46:52.276
a part of America's leadership
in space exploration.

00:46:52.276 --> 00:46:55.746
Through the American-style
commercial pathway,

00:46:55.746 --> 00:46:58.382
I am certain we will
continue to inspire

00:46:58.382 --> 00:47:00.784
the next generation
of explorers,

00:47:00.784 --> 00:47:04.454
so that one day, those students
from Crown Point, Indiana,

00:47:04.454 --> 00:47:07.791
will be standing in front
of a future space council

00:47:08.759 --> 00:47:12.095
discussing how the United States
commercial lunar base

00:47:12.095 --> 00:47:14.031
is just another place
to do business.

00:47:14.031 --> 00:47:16.033
So, thank you.

00:47:16.033 --> 00:47:22.706
(Applause.)

00:47:22.706 --> 00:47:24.274
The Vice President:
Thank you, Jeffery; well said.

00:47:24.942 --> 00:47:27.811
And Bhavya Lal recognized,

00:47:27.811 --> 00:47:29.112
and then we'll move
on to questions

00:47:29.112 --> 00:47:31.114
after your presentation.

00:47:31.114 --> 00:47:32.716
Ms. Lal: Good morning,
Mr. Vice President,

00:47:32.716 --> 00:47:34.985
and members of
the National Space Council.

00:47:35.586 --> 00:47:37.487
A discussion
on the threats to U.S.

00:47:37.487 --> 00:47:41.792
competitiveness in space needs
to start with acknowledgment

00:47:41.792 --> 00:47:44.595
that we are the preeminent space
power in the world today.

00:47:45.395 --> 00:47:48.298
The U.S. government
still spends more on space

00:47:48.298 --> 00:47:50.200
than the rest of the governments
in the world combined.

00:47:50.867 --> 00:47:53.403
The United States has more
satellites and other assets

00:47:53.403 --> 00:47:55.772
in orbit than any other
country in the world.

00:47:56.373 --> 00:47:59.109
The world's current
most powerful rocket

00:47:59.109 --> 00:48:02.746
launch just two weeks ago is
a product of American industry.

00:48:03.413 --> 00:48:04.948
A recent study in global trends

00:48:04.948 --> 00:48:06.984
in small satellites
by my organization,

00:48:06.984 --> 00:48:09.119
the IDA Science and Technology
Policy Institute,

00:48:09.620 --> 00:48:12.389
found that about two thirds
of the hundred organizations

00:48:12.389 --> 00:48:14.024
doing the most
innovative R&amp;D

00:48:14.024 --> 00:48:16.526
in the small-sat sector
are U.S.-based.

00:48:17.361 --> 00:48:20.430
These advantages, however,
cannot be taken for granted,

00:48:20.964 --> 00:48:24.735
and our leadership in space is
increasingly being challenged.

00:48:25.469 --> 00:48:28.105
Global investments in space
have steadily grown

00:48:28.105 --> 00:48:29.873
over the past two decades.

00:48:29.873 --> 00:48:33.076
A decade ago, for instance,
fewer than 50 countries

00:48:33.076 --> 00:48:35.812
were investing about
40 billion dollars in space.

00:48:36.413 --> 00:48:41.051
By 2026, 30 more countries are
expected to join the space club,

00:48:41.051 --> 00:48:42.986
and global expenditures
are expected

00:48:42.986 --> 00:48:45.055
to double those
of 10 years ago.

00:48:46.490 --> 00:48:48.392
Growing
international expenditure

00:48:48.392 --> 00:48:50.594
is only one development
in the space sector.

00:48:51.328 --> 00:48:53.130
Partially as a result
of investments

00:48:53.130 --> 00:48:55.132
from the U.S. government,

00:48:55.132 --> 00:48:57.534
there have been dramatic
improvements in the technology

00:48:57.534 --> 00:48:59.136
used in the space sector.

00:48:59.136 --> 00:49:02.239
In some areas, costs have
fallen orders of magnitude.

00:49:03.106 --> 00:49:05.475
Using a combination
of alternative architectures,

00:49:05.475 --> 00:49:07.744
such as swarms of
hundreds of satellites,

00:49:07.744 --> 00:49:09.713
and business process innovation,

00:49:09.713 --> 00:49:13.150
relatively inexpensive
breadbox-sized satellites

00:49:13.150 --> 00:49:16.186
are able to nearly
match services

00:49:16.186 --> 00:49:19.890
that were previously feasible
only with bus-sized satellites

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:22.626
that cost hundreds of millions,
if not billions, of dollars.

00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:26.063
Buoyed by the perception
of profitability,

00:49:26.063 --> 00:49:29.700
space has become an attractive
target for private investment:

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:32.869
almost 17 billion dollars
since 2000,

00:49:32.869 --> 00:49:35.439
and four billion in 2017 alone.

00:49:36.406 --> 00:49:39.743
As a result, some sectors
of space are transitioning

00:49:39.743 --> 00:49:42.846
from a top-down
government-fed operation

00:49:42.846 --> 00:49:44.214
to a globalized industry

00:49:44.214 --> 00:49:46.783
with worldwide supply
chains and customers.

00:49:47.451 --> 00:49:51.455
Using both domestic investment
and products and services

00:49:51.455 --> 00:49:53.990
from this rapidly
growing private sector,

00:49:53.990 --> 00:49:56.026
the rest of the world
is leapfrogging

00:49:56.593 --> 00:49:59.162
decades-worth
of technological development

00:49:59.162 --> 00:50:01.164
aiming to build systems
that can compete

00:50:01.164 --> 00:50:02.866
with the United States
in many areas,

00:50:02.866 --> 00:50:05.702
including launch,
robotic space operations,

00:50:05.702 --> 00:50:07.037
and even human exploration.

00:50:07.704 --> 00:50:10.807
My central point is that threats
to U.S. leadership in space

00:50:10.807 --> 00:50:14.678
have arisen primarily from
these structural changes

00:50:14.678 --> 00:50:16.446
that are enabling
many more countries

00:50:16.446 --> 00:50:19.049
to target and achieve
success in space.

00:50:19.049 --> 00:50:20.550
And there is no turning
back the clock.

00:50:21.551 --> 00:50:23.720
In this environment,
maintaining U.S. leadership

00:50:23.720 --> 00:50:26.123
means that the United States,
more than ever,

00:50:26.123 --> 00:50:29.393
needs to leverage its core
competitive advantage,

00:50:29.393 --> 00:50:32.129
an innovation ecosystem
that rewards creativity,

00:50:32.129 --> 00:50:34.030
entrepreneurship,
and risk-taking.

00:50:34.798 --> 00:50:36.066
Going beyond the fundamental,

00:50:36.066 --> 00:50:38.034
there are some space
sector specific actions

00:50:38.034 --> 00:50:39.236
that would be relevant as well.

00:50:39.836 --> 00:50:41.271
I propose we begin with three:

00:50:41.772 --> 00:50:44.708
ensure that our regulations
empower the U.S. private sector

00:50:44.708 --> 00:50:47.043
to continue to out-innovate
the rest of the world;

00:50:47.577 --> 00:50:49.980
ensure government spending
is more efficient;

00:50:49.980 --> 00:50:52.949
and invest in capabilities
where we absolutely

00:50:52.949 --> 00:50:54.818
must have overwhelming advantage

00:50:54.818 --> 00:50:56.119
over other countries.

00:50:56.119 --> 00:50:58.455
I look forward to contributing
to this discussion.

00:50:58.455 --> 00:51:07.397
(Applause.)

00:51:07.397 --> 00:51:09.065
The Vice President: Well, I 
want to thank all the panelists,

00:51:09.065 --> 00:51:15.338
so I'm going to go to several
of our security members

00:51:15.338 --> 00:51:17.941
of the council
who are with us today,

00:51:18.575 --> 00:51:24.047
but let me, maybe, direct my
first question to Dr. Lal.

00:51:24.047 --> 00:51:30.654
Your -- you have spoken about
the challenges that we face.

00:51:31.221 --> 00:51:33.356
You refer to
structural challenges;

00:51:33.356 --> 00:51:34.458
there's no going back;

00:51:34.458 --> 00:51:37.761
the United States has to
continue to lean in to remain,

00:51:38.962 --> 00:51:41.431
to use your words,
a preeminent leader in space.

00:51:43.133 --> 00:51:47.671
You have written and spoken
about space traffic management.

00:51:47.671 --> 00:51:51.408
Is there a policy decision
you would have this council

00:51:51.408 --> 00:51:53.877
consider related to that,

00:51:54.978 --> 00:51:57.547
and could you expand
on that briefly?

00:51:58.248 --> 00:51:59.850
Ms. Lal: Sure.

00:51:59.850 --> 00:52:02.886
So, space traffic management
is a very critical component

00:52:02.886 --> 00:52:05.055
of our private sector
leadership in space,

00:52:05.555 --> 00:52:08.925
primarily because
it gives us the clarity --

00:52:08.925 --> 00:52:11.261
it gives the companies
the clarity they need

00:52:11.261 --> 00:52:13.430
to do unfettered work in space.

00:52:13.430 --> 00:52:15.565
It allows us to work
collaboratively

00:52:15.565 --> 00:52:17.334
with other countries,

00:52:17.334 --> 00:52:19.336
especially if we have a fabric

00:52:19.336 --> 00:52:21.838
of the management
system that is --

00:52:21.838 --> 00:52:24.541
that joins with each other,

00:52:25.041 --> 00:52:28.512
and there is agreement
across the world

00:52:28.512 --> 00:52:30.213
as to how we want to go forward

00:52:31.081 --> 00:52:35.452
to make sure that space is safe
and sustainable to operate in.

00:52:36.453 --> 00:52:38.054
The Vice President:
It --

00:52:38.054 --> 00:52:40.023
I've got people
who know a lot more

00:52:40.023 --> 00:52:41.491
about this than me
at this table,

00:52:41.491 --> 00:52:45.729
but it sounds to me like you're
calling on the United States

00:52:45.729 --> 00:52:49.065
to play a wider role in ensuring

00:52:49.065 --> 00:52:52.002
that we have the same kind
of deconfliction agreements

00:52:52.002 --> 00:52:54.604
that we have in areas
of conflict

00:52:55.205 --> 00:53:00.377
that we have in terms of issues
of navigation on the seven seas,

00:53:00.377 --> 00:53:02.646
and that you're suggesting
that the United States

00:53:03.446 --> 00:53:06.449
lean in to that effort
and provide that guidance

00:53:06.449 --> 00:53:07.784
and drive those agreements.
Ms. Lal:

00:53:08.318 --> 00:53:10.186
I absolutely think
the United States

00:53:10.186 --> 00:53:12.022
needs to take
a leadership position here.

00:53:12.022 --> 00:53:13.924
The Vice President:
Yeah.

00:53:13.924 --> 00:53:16.092
Very insightful;
appreciate that very much.

00:53:16.092 --> 00:53:19.796
The Deputy Secretary of Defense
is with us today, Pat Shanahan.

00:53:19.796 --> 00:53:21.464
Mr. Secretary,
would you like to --

00:53:22.566 --> 00:53:25.769
Deputy Secretary Shanahan:
A quick question there for Dean.

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:27.938
Thank you for your remarks
this morning.

00:53:29.439 --> 00:53:34.077
My question is around
civil/military partnerships

00:53:34.077 --> 00:53:36.379
that you've observed in China,

00:53:36.379 --> 00:53:39.215
and maybe it's not
just civil/military

00:53:39.215 --> 00:53:41.284
but industrial/military.

00:53:42.218 --> 00:53:47.123
Have you seen a different
dynamic in the partnerships

00:53:47.824 --> 00:53:50.327
that we should observe,
or take notice of?

00:53:53.296 --> 00:53:56.566
Mr. Cheng: The Chinese 
have published extensively

00:53:56.566 --> 00:53:59.369
on the issues of things
like mobilization,

00:54:00.003 --> 00:54:01.338
where they include things

00:54:01.338 --> 00:54:03.573
like science and technology
mobilization.

00:54:03.573 --> 00:54:06.543
So, there is an explicit
organizational structure,

00:54:07.043 --> 00:54:09.145
regulatory structure, et cetera,

00:54:09.145 --> 00:54:12.916
for the incorporation
of people, equipment,

00:54:12.916 --> 00:54:14.517
as well as facilities.

00:54:14.517 --> 00:54:17.087
So, when we think about
China's space program,

00:54:17.087 --> 00:54:21.257
we should be thinking of it not
simply in terms of the elements

00:54:21.257 --> 00:54:23.393
that are currently
in the military,

00:54:23.393 --> 00:54:24.928
but the reach-back
that the Chinese

00:54:24.928 --> 00:54:26.896
have explicitly talked about,

00:54:26.896 --> 00:54:29.933
in terms of bringing in
everything from universities,

00:54:29.933 --> 00:54:31.801
to corporate assets,

00:54:31.801 --> 00:54:34.304
to industrial personnel
and equipment.

00:54:35.338 --> 00:54:36.439
Deputy Secretary Shanahan:
Thank you.

00:54:39.376 --> 00:54:41.277
The Vice President: We're fortunate to have with us today --

00:54:41.277 --> 00:54:42.812
I know he was
formally introduced,

00:54:42.812 --> 00:54:44.547
but Chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff,

00:54:45.615 --> 00:54:47.017
General Joseph Dunford.

00:54:47.017 --> 00:54:49.085
You could welcome him
one more time, if you'd like.

00:54:49.085 --> 00:54:50.387
He is an extraordinary --

00:54:50.387 --> 00:54:53.156
(Applause.)

00:54:53.156 --> 00:54:55.225
The Vice President:
General?

00:54:55.225 --> 00:54:57.527
General Dunford:
I have a question

00:54:57.527 --> 00:54:58.595
for Mr. Manber.

00:54:58.595 --> 00:55:02.832
You talked about not allowing
concerns over technology

00:55:02.832 --> 00:55:05.335
transfer to inhibit
our progress,

00:55:05.335 --> 00:55:08.038
but, you know, it struck me
as I was listening

00:55:08.038 --> 00:55:11.775
to the recap of the strategy
from General McMaster

00:55:11.775 --> 00:55:14.044
that we are going
to have concerns

00:55:14.044 --> 00:55:16.346
over protecting our
intellectual property

00:55:16.346 --> 00:55:17.714
and our classified information.

00:55:18.248 --> 00:55:19.983
And I wonder, from
an industry perspective,

00:55:19.983 --> 00:55:21.885
with now three
decades of experience,

00:55:21.885 --> 00:55:23.486
you can maybe
talk a little bit

00:55:23.486 --> 00:55:25.088
about how do we get
that balance right?

00:55:25.088 --> 00:55:27.290
Because, again, as
we implement the strategy,

00:55:27.290 --> 00:55:29.426
we ought to think
about that up front,

00:55:30.460 --> 00:55:32.228
and make sure that we do that.

00:55:32.228 --> 00:55:33.830
And I -- I'm particularly
struck by it

00:55:33.830 --> 00:55:36.032
because of the brief on China,

00:55:36.032 --> 00:55:38.835
and although you say that
most of their capabilities

00:55:38.835 --> 00:55:40.103
are indigenous
and homegrown.

00:55:40.904 --> 00:55:43.573
That would actually be unique
in Chinese experience

00:55:43.573 --> 00:55:45.875
that most of their current,
modern capabilities

00:55:45.875 --> 00:55:47.844
are indigenous and homegrown
because I think we know

00:55:47.844 --> 00:55:50.447
that we've had intellectual
property challenge,

00:55:50.447 --> 00:55:52.382
and a classified information
challenge, with China.

00:55:52.382 --> 00:55:53.817
So, maybe, Mr. Manber,

00:55:53.817 --> 00:55:57.220
you're probably the best
one to address that,

00:55:57.220 --> 00:55:58.755
and, again, it's about
getting the balance right.

00:55:58.755 --> 00:56:00.156
Mr. Manber: Right, it's 
a fascinating question

00:56:01.725 --> 00:56:03.326
and thank you for it.

00:56:03.326 --> 00:56:05.295
It's very difficult
in our industry

00:56:06.229 --> 00:56:09.265
to strike the right balance
between competitiveness

00:56:09.265 --> 00:56:10.767
and assuring that, you know,

00:56:10.767 --> 00:56:12.936
America safeguards
its technology.

00:56:13.837 --> 00:56:18.041
But I suppose that
we have already worked

00:56:18.041 --> 00:56:20.343
with NASA very carefully,
and others,

00:56:20.343 --> 00:56:22.746
to ensure that there's
no technology transfer.

00:56:23.513 --> 00:56:26.916
We work very closely
to assure that they learn,

00:56:26.916 --> 00:56:30.086
the Chinese and other
of the nations we work with --

00:56:30.086 --> 00:56:32.122
I said we work
with some 30 nations;

00:56:32.122 --> 00:56:34.958
they've included Viet Nam,
Peru, and others --

00:56:34.958 --> 00:56:36.893
that there is
no technology transfer,

00:56:37.660 --> 00:56:39.796
that the guidelines
and practices

00:56:39.796 --> 00:56:41.831
of the International
Space Station

00:56:41.831 --> 00:56:43.166
remain confidential.

00:56:44.367 --> 00:56:47.604
At the same time, we see
that just a few weeks ago,

00:56:47.604 --> 00:56:51.174
there's Canadian satellites
launching with the Chinese,

00:56:51.174 --> 00:56:54.144
there's Danish companies
that are developing satellites

00:56:54.144 --> 00:56:56.246
that are flying
with the Chinese.

00:56:57.981 --> 00:57:01.718
My point is that if we go in
with American leadership,

00:57:01.718 --> 00:57:05.188
and we go in and we can say
to the Chinese,

00:57:05.188 --> 00:57:08.892
"Here is the issues that
we regard as important in IP,

00:57:08.892 --> 00:57:11.027
copyright protection,
technology transfer,"

00:57:11.961 --> 00:57:13.963
there is when we have
the greatest strength,

00:57:13.963 --> 00:57:17.066
starting new, starting
with a new marketplace,

00:57:17.066 --> 00:57:18.902
to ensure that we get
what we need.

00:57:19.836 --> 00:57:22.539
And as the President has said,
we want to, you know, revamp

00:57:22.539 --> 00:57:24.908
and reconsider
our relations with China.

00:57:24.908 --> 00:57:28.411
And so, I can see no better
opportunity than to do it here,

00:57:28.411 --> 00:57:30.113
where we're not involved today,

00:57:30.113 --> 00:57:32.215
but we're clearly leaders
of the free world.

00:57:33.349 --> 00:57:35.351
General Dunford:
Yeah, thank you.

00:57:36.186 --> 00:57:37.453
The Vice President:
Secretary of Homeland Security

00:57:37.453 --> 00:57:39.889
Kirstjen Nielsen is recognized,
thank you, Kirstjen.

00:57:40.423 --> 00:57:41.524
Secretary Nielsen:
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

00:57:41.524 --> 00:57:43.326
Good morning,
and thank you to the panelists.

00:57:44.093 --> 00:57:45.795
My question is just
for all of you.

00:57:46.362 --> 00:57:48.565
As the Secretary of the
Department of Homeland Security,

00:57:48.565 --> 00:57:52.101
we care deeply about
space-based services,

00:57:52.101 --> 00:57:54.971
everything from the weather
and the satellites

00:57:54.971 --> 00:57:57.273
that we get from NOAA
in the Commerce Department,

00:57:57.841 --> 00:58:00.443
through to our ability
to warn our citizens,

00:58:00.443 --> 00:58:01.744
through to cyber security

00:58:01.744 --> 00:58:04.047
and then very specific
space-based services

00:58:04.047 --> 00:58:06.950
such as GPS-enabled position
navigation and timing.

00:58:07.584 --> 00:58:09.352
So, of concern to me
is making sure

00:58:09.352 --> 00:58:11.187
that as we work
with the private sector

00:58:11.187 --> 00:58:13.156
and as the U.S.
government moves forward,

00:58:13.156 --> 00:58:16.693
that we continue to build
in security and resilience

00:58:16.693 --> 00:58:18.361
into all of our tools.

00:58:18.361 --> 00:58:20.496
What more can
the U.S. government do,

00:58:20.496 --> 00:58:22.866
from your perspective,
to incentivize,

00:58:22.866 --> 00:58:24.033
as we go forward,

00:58:24.033 --> 00:58:25.501
that security and resilience

00:58:25.501 --> 00:58:27.136
in all of our
space-based services

00:58:27.136 --> 00:58:28.638
upon which we're
so heavily reliant?

00:58:31.741 --> 00:58:33.309
Ms. Lal:
So, I would say

00:58:33.309 --> 00:58:35.144
it would be helpful
for the government

00:58:35.144 --> 00:58:37.513
to work more with
the private sector,

00:58:37.513 --> 00:58:39.449
especially the part
of the private sector

00:58:39.449 --> 00:58:41.818
that typically hasn't been
in the government fold.

00:58:42.418 --> 00:58:45.088
And one way to do that
would be to make sure

00:58:45.088 --> 00:58:48.157
that the government uses
more commercial approaches,

00:58:48.157 --> 00:58:49.525
you know, things that, you know,

00:58:49.525 --> 00:58:53.296
not necessarily
cost-plus type contracts

00:58:53.296 --> 00:58:57.934
but ones that are more
solutions are outcome-driven

00:58:57.934 --> 00:59:01.304
where there's milestones and
payments based on milestones.

00:59:01.838 --> 00:59:03.606
Another alternative would be,

00:59:03.606 --> 00:59:06.376
another activity
to add would be,

00:59:06.910 --> 00:59:09.445
to be able to accept
80 percent solutions,

00:59:10.113 --> 00:59:12.916
because that would just
really improve the aperture

00:59:14.250 --> 00:59:16.352
with the kind of companies
you can work with.

00:59:16.352 --> 00:59:18.221
We don't always need
to have a Ferrari;

00:59:18.221 --> 00:59:19.956
we can sometimes
use a Ford Focus.

00:59:21.925 --> 00:59:23.793
Mr. Manber:
I'll just quickly add that

00:59:23.793 --> 00:59:26.396
from our experience
at NanoRocks,

00:59:26.396 --> 00:59:28.998
we have a very robust
relationship with NASA

00:59:28.998 --> 00:59:30.233
on all levels.

00:59:30.233 --> 00:59:33.503
And having this sort
of partnership is critical.

00:59:34.337 --> 00:59:37.173
We always are
in lockstep with NASA

00:59:37.173 --> 00:59:39.709
on what we're doing,
especially as we go overseas.

00:59:40.376 --> 00:59:42.245
And you have to, you know,
there's emerging

00:59:42.245 --> 00:59:46.582
throughout the U.S. government
great folks who care,

00:59:47.083 --> 00:59:49.452
more than just getting up
and doing their job.

00:59:49.452 --> 00:59:51.921
And this is at DOD,
this is at NASA,

00:59:51.921 --> 00:59:53.289
and they really work with us

00:59:53.289 --> 00:59:56.759
to make sure that we don't
overstep what might be proper.

00:59:56.759 --> 00:59:58.561
We're always itching
to do more, of course;

00:59:58.561 --> 00:59:59.762
it's the commercial sector.

01:00:00.496 --> 01:00:02.198
But you have to have
the relationships

01:00:02.198 --> 01:00:04.767
with the government officials
and the government folks.

01:00:04.767 --> 01:00:07.170
And so, we really appreciate
our relationship with NASA.

01:00:07.170 --> 01:00:08.871
And so, passing this along,

01:00:08.871 --> 01:00:12.342
I would say it's not something
maybe you can codify.

01:00:12.342 --> 01:00:14.410
You just have to have
an organize relationship

01:00:14.410 --> 01:00:16.946
to be smarter,
to be alert,

01:00:16.946 --> 01:00:18.548
and don't consider
the government,

01:00:18.548 --> 01:00:20.083
always, as the enemy,

01:00:20.083 --> 01:00:22.585
but work with them on these
sort of critical issues.

01:00:24.787 --> 01:00:26.456
Mr. Cheng:
Ma'am, I would say that one

01:00:26.456 --> 01:00:27.991
of the things to keep in mind

01:00:27.991 --> 01:00:32.395
is that space is part of
a larger information ecosystem.

01:00:33.062 --> 01:00:35.598
The Chinese view space
very holistically.

01:00:35.598 --> 01:00:37.700
When they talk about space
and space dominance,

01:00:37.700 --> 01:00:39.736
they are talking not
only about satellites,

01:00:39.736 --> 01:00:40.770
but ground stations,

01:00:40.770 --> 01:00:42.672
and the data links
that tie them all together,

01:00:42.672 --> 01:00:44.941
as well as the information
that passes over it.

01:00:44.941 --> 01:00:46.376
When we think about resilience,

01:00:46.376 --> 01:00:49.412
then, we need to be
thinking beyond just space.

01:00:49.412 --> 01:00:51.114
We need to be thinking
about redundancies,

01:00:51.114 --> 01:00:53.116
whether it's things
like EE Loran,

01:00:53.116 --> 01:00:55.718
or other alternatives
that may not be orbital.

01:00:55.718 --> 01:00:57.453
And when we think
about protecting

01:00:57.453 --> 01:00:59.088
our space capabilities,

01:00:59.088 --> 01:01:01.257
it means, again,
thinking holistically

01:01:01.257 --> 01:01:03.793
because it's really about
the information that passes

01:01:03.793 --> 01:01:05.695
over and through
those space systems.

01:01:09.499 --> 01:01:11.067
The Vice President:
Join me in thanking these

01:01:11.067 --> 01:01:12.101
outstanding panelists

01:01:12.101 --> 01:01:15.138
for their inights and 
participation in the program.

01:01:15.138 --> 01:01:16.572
(Applause.)

01:01:16.572 --> 01:01:17.907
Thank you, all,
great job, great job.

01:01:17.907 --> 01:01:21.978
(Applause.)

