The next panel is
entitled entrepreneurship

01:01:27.150 --> 01:01:28.351
on the next frontier.

01:01:28.351 --> 01:01:30.787
I'll invite our
panelists to go ahead

01:01:30.787 --> 01:01:33.589
and make your way
to the stage.

01:01:34.490 --> 01:01:35.892
And before we get started,

01:01:35.892 --> 01:01:40.096
let me just say
to all the members

01:01:40.096 --> 01:01:42.765
of the National Space Council.

01:01:42.765 --> 01:01:45.668
I think we've heard some very
insightful recommendations.

01:01:45.668 --> 01:01:50.073
And particularly, would request
General McMaster that --

01:01:51.407 --> 01:01:56.312
if you could develop a plan
that identifies additional steps

01:01:56.312 --> 01:01:59.415
derived from
the discussion today

01:01:59.415 --> 01:02:01.717
that ought to be added
to our space strategy.

01:02:01.717 --> 01:02:05.054
We'll look forward
to your presentation

01:02:05.054 --> 01:02:09.225
on that at the next
National Space Council meeting.

01:02:12.795 --> 01:02:15.264
They've written me very
thoughtful opening remarks

01:02:15.264 --> 01:02:17.467
about entrepreneurship
and the next frontier.

01:02:18.835 --> 01:02:23.606
But in the interest of time,
let me be brief and say,

01:02:23.606 --> 01:02:28.578
President Trump
is for it, all right?

01:02:28.578 --> 01:02:30.480
I was on the phone with
the President yesterday,

01:02:30.480 --> 01:02:32.882
and this businessman turned
President of the United States

01:02:32.882 --> 01:02:35.184
has great pride
and great enthusiasm

01:02:36.085 --> 01:02:39.155
in not only the partnership,
the historic partnership

01:02:39.856 --> 01:02:43.626
between private sector
organizations and NASA,

01:02:44.127 --> 01:02:47.196
but also great pride
in the development

01:02:47.196 --> 01:02:48.898
of new platforms
and innovation

01:02:49.966 --> 01:02:53.236
that we saw just two weeks
ahead with the Falcon Heavy,

01:02:53.236 --> 01:02:57.106
and that we see in all the names
of all the different rockets

01:02:57.106 --> 01:02:59.675
that we talked about
in my presentation today.

01:02:59.675 --> 01:03:04.080
I was at the Mojave Desert,
and visited the --

01:03:04.947 --> 01:03:06.816
another American space port.

01:03:06.816 --> 01:03:10.153
And I can't help but think,
100 years from now,

01:03:12.455 --> 01:03:15.358
it will be our private
sector pioneers

01:03:16.292 --> 01:03:18.561
that helped lift America

01:03:18.561 --> 01:03:22.165
into this new era
of space exploration,

01:03:22.165 --> 01:03:24.634
just as American pioneers
have done in the past.

01:03:24.634 --> 01:03:27.069
So, that said, I just
want to express

01:03:27.069 --> 01:03:28.738
a great enthusiasm
in President Trump,

01:03:28.738 --> 01:03:30.907
the great gratitude
to this distinguished panel,

01:03:32.241 --> 01:03:33.543
and let me introduce them all,

01:03:33.543 --> 01:03:35.111
and then invite you
to give them a welcome.

01:03:35.778 --> 01:03:36.646
In the interest of time,

01:03:36.646 --> 01:03:39.515
I'll ask the panelists
to summarize your remarks.

01:03:39.515 --> 01:03:41.250
We'll have time
for a few questions

01:03:41.250 --> 01:03:43.886
before we're spirited
off to a tour,

01:03:43.886 --> 01:03:45.488
and I have to wing my way,

01:03:45.488 --> 01:03:46.822
with many of these
Cabinet officials,

01:03:46.822 --> 01:03:48.824
back to Washington, D.C.

01:03:49.926 --> 01:03:52.128
Our first panelist
is Mr. Eric Stallmer,

01:03:52.128 --> 01:03:54.397
president of Commercial
Spaceflight Federation,

01:03:55.097 --> 01:03:59.202
one of our hosts here today
for events last evening.

01:03:59.869 --> 01:04:01.404
Secondly is Kevin O'Connell,

01:04:01.404 --> 01:04:03.306
president of Innovative
Analytics Training.

01:04:04.240 --> 01:04:05.408
Then, there's Tom Stroup,

01:04:05.408 --> 01:04:07.443
president of Satellite
Industry Association.

01:04:07.443 --> 01:04:08.377
And our fourth panelist

01:04:08.377 --> 01:04:10.947
is Dr. Mary Lynne Dittmar,

01:04:10.947 --> 01:04:15.017
president and CEO of the 
Coalition for Deep Space Exploration.

01:04:15.017 --> 01:04:17.553
These are the four
great champions

01:04:17.553 --> 01:04:19.322
of American
entrepreneurship in space,

01:04:19.322 --> 01:04:20.590
and we're honored
to have you all here.

01:04:20.590 --> 01:04:22.592
Thank you so very much.

01:04:22.592 --> 01:04:26.862
(Applause.)

01:04:26.862 --> 01:04:28.564
Mr. Stallmer, if you
could get it started,

01:04:28.564 --> 01:04:30.366
and briefly summarize
your remarks,

01:04:30.366 --> 01:04:31.634
we'll move through
the panel quickly.

01:04:31.634 --> 01:04:33.102
Thank you.

01:04:33.102 --> 01:04:34.303
Mr. Stallmer:
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

01:04:34.904 --> 01:04:37.707
Cabinet secretaries and members
of the National Space Council,

01:04:37.707 --> 01:04:39.308
thank you so much
for giving me the opportunity

01:04:39.308 --> 01:04:41.077
to be here today.

01:04:41.077 --> 01:04:42.612
America's commercial
space sector

01:04:42.612 --> 01:04:44.180
is growing at a pace
and breadth,

01:04:44.780 --> 01:04:46.616
creating thousands
of high-tech jobs

01:04:46.616 --> 01:04:49.285
driven by billions of dollars
of private sector investment.

01:04:50.052 --> 01:04:52.955
Last year, we witnessed
many breakthrough capabilities

01:04:52.955 --> 01:04:54.724
by U.S. commercial
space companies.

01:04:55.224 --> 01:04:57.293
And just recently,
as we discussed today,

01:04:57.293 --> 01:04:58.961
just last week --
or a few weeks ago,

01:04:58.961 --> 01:05:01.330
SpaceX launched
its Falcon Heavy,

01:05:01.330 --> 01:05:03.366
the first heavy
lift rocket developed

01:05:03.366 --> 01:05:05.067
and launched with
fully private funding.

01:05:05.668 --> 01:05:08.070
And Blue Origin flew
its new Shepard to space

01:05:08.070 --> 01:05:12.008
under the new RLV license,
the first such revenue flight.

01:05:12.008 --> 01:05:14.510
They're also developing
their own heavy lift vehicle

01:05:14.510 --> 01:05:16.412
with private sector funding --
with private funding.

01:05:17.713 --> 01:05:20.516
But two significant challenges
threaten America's goals

01:05:20.516 --> 01:05:22.818
in expanding
our economic sphere and --

01:05:22.818 --> 01:05:27.723
deepening into space:
commercial space transportation

01:05:27.723 --> 01:05:30.393
and remote sensing are growing
at unprecedented rated,

01:05:31.160 --> 01:05:34.463
while new space applications,
like space manufacturing,

01:05:34.463 --> 01:05:37.133
resource prospecting,
and human habitation,

01:05:37.133 --> 01:05:38.901
are being introduced.

01:05:38.901 --> 01:05:41.871
As discussed earlier,
our legal and regulatory

01:05:41.871 --> 01:05:44.473
and organizational frameworks
have not caught up

01:05:44.473 --> 01:05:47.310
and are putting on the brakes
on our current progress,

01:05:47.310 --> 01:05:49.078
as well as our
future possibilities.

01:05:50.446 --> 01:05:52.181
We need to strive
for what economists

01:05:52.181 --> 01:05:55.318
call permission-less
innovation in spaceflight.

01:05:56.018 --> 01:05:59.021
So long as public safety,
international obligations,

01:05:59.021 --> 01:06:01.390
and national security
are not compromised,

01:06:01.390 --> 01:06:04.126
the presumption should be
that a commercial space project

01:06:04.126 --> 01:06:05.661
can proceed.

