and re-entry
to protect the public

01:06:08.831 --> 01:06:10.633
definitely warrant
a licensed regime;

01:06:11.334 --> 01:06:13.102
however, the current
regulations,

01:06:13.102 --> 01:06:14.403
written decades ago,

01:06:14.403 --> 01:06:17.473
based on 1980s technologies
and operations,

01:06:18.074 --> 01:06:20.476
those rockets were expendable,
very expensive,

01:06:20.976 --> 01:06:23.746
and infrequently launched,
and carried only one payloads.

01:06:24.814 --> 01:06:28.517
Space ports also faced
inconsistent interpretations

01:06:28.517 --> 01:06:30.119
of regulations
and requirements.

01:06:30.753 --> 01:06:33.155
The same rules that are
required to be implement --

01:06:33.155 --> 01:06:34.924
the same rules are required
to be implemented

01:06:34.924 --> 01:06:36.926
differently at different
launch sites.

01:06:37.693 --> 01:06:41.263
And even modest improvements
to space ports infrastructure

01:06:41.263 --> 01:06:43.766
can require new rounds
of environmental review

01:06:43.766 --> 01:06:47.103
because it modifies the launch
site operator's license.

01:06:48.137 --> 01:06:50.806
Our members at CSF at eager
to work with the administration

01:06:50.806 --> 01:06:53.843
to modernize and streamline
various licensing rules

01:06:53.843 --> 01:06:57.813
into one performance-based rule
that preserves public safety

01:06:57.813 --> 01:07:00.783
without restricting industry
speed and flexibility

01:07:00.783 --> 01:07:03.986
to invent a future where
launchers are more frequent,

01:07:03.986 --> 01:07:06.088
more affordable,
and certainly, more reliable.

01:07:06.889 --> 01:07:10.426
In many cases, rules can be made
clearer and more concise,

01:07:10.426 --> 01:07:12.695
with explanatory details
left to guidance.

01:07:13.996 --> 01:07:15.364
Remote sensing, in particular,

01:07:15.364 --> 01:07:18.067
has been constrained
by outdated regulations

01:07:18.067 --> 01:07:19.935
that often aren't
faithfully implemented.

01:07:21.036 --> 01:07:22.838
And finally, it's time for
the federal government

01:07:22.838 --> 01:07:24.840
to create a minimalistic process

01:07:24.840 --> 01:07:27.777
for improving new
commercial space activities

01:07:27.777 --> 01:07:29.745
by U.S. companies.

01:07:29.745 --> 01:07:32.381
H.R. 2809 provides
narrowly tailored

01:07:32.381 --> 01:07:35.050
approach to government
oversight of those activities,

01:07:35.050 --> 01:07:37.253
which why CSF has
endorsed this passage.

01:07:38.287 --> 01:07:39.855
With commercial
space industry --

01:07:40.456 --> 01:07:42.425
with a commercial space
industry unleashed

01:07:42.425 --> 01:07:44.059
to advance quickly
as possible,

01:07:44.660 --> 01:07:46.629
the U.S. government
needs to adapt

01:07:46.629 --> 01:07:48.330
to gain the maximum
public benefit.

01:07:48.864 --> 01:07:50.699
Commercial companies
can deliver results

01:07:50.699 --> 01:07:53.035
faster and cheaper
for taxpayers,

01:07:53.035 --> 01:07:55.671
but only a federal agency
can use commercial friendly

01:07:55.671 --> 01:07:58.207
procurement methods
that pay for results,

01:07:58.207 --> 01:07:59.975
not for it -- just effort.

01:07:59.975 --> 01:08:01.610
For example, NASA
should be encouraged

01:08:01.610 --> 01:08:03.045
to use competitively-awarded,

01:08:03.045 --> 01:08:05.548
cost-shared funded
Space Act agreements

01:08:05.548 --> 01:08:08.417
to develop new space
exploration capabilities

01:08:08.417 --> 01:08:11.053
so that the United States
can affordably accelerate

01:08:11.053 --> 01:08:12.254
a return to the moon,

01:08:12.254 --> 01:08:14.223
and voyages beyond.

01:08:14.223 --> 01:08:17.126
All space-related agencies
should ask the question:

01:08:17.126 --> 01:08:18.194
can we partner?

01:08:18.194 --> 01:08:21.030
Before taking the traditional
cost plus contracting path.

01:08:22.164 --> 01:08:26.268
In conclusion, America's
industrial paradigm for space

01:08:26.268 --> 01:08:29.138
has fundamentally changed,
developing to a point

01:08:29.138 --> 01:08:30.606
where the U.S.
government regulations

01:08:30.606 --> 01:08:33.676
and contracting practices
are now our largest impediments.

01:08:34.343 --> 01:08:37.313
Now, more than ever, we need
the National Space Council,

01:08:37.313 --> 01:08:39.982
and we need you to take action
and work with industry.

01:08:39.982 --> 01:08:41.984
Thank you so much
for your time.

01:08:41.984 --> 01:08:51.627
(Applause.)

01:08:51.627 --> 01:08:52.761
The Vice President: Thank you
very much, Mr. Stallmer.

01:08:52.761 --> 01:08:54.530
Mr. O'Connell,
you're recognized.

01:08:54.530 --> 01:08:55.764
Mr. O'Connell:
Mr. Vice President,

01:08:55.764 --> 01:09:01.136
distinguished Cabinet members,
invited guests, good morning.

01:09:01.136 --> 01:09:02.872
My name is Kevin O'Connell.

01:09:02.872 --> 01:09:05.708
I am the founder and CEO
of Innovative Analytics

01:09:05.708 --> 01:09:06.809
and Training,

01:09:06.809 --> 01:09:08.911
a small private consulting
firm in Washington, D.C.

01:09:09.678 --> 01:09:11.447
Today, I'm going to
bring forward to you

01:09:11.447 --> 01:09:13.716
my 25 years of writing

01:09:13.716 --> 01:09:16.352
and analyzing commercial
remote sensing

01:09:16.352 --> 01:09:18.287
for both government
and commercial clients.

01:09:19.088 --> 01:09:20.389
I'd like to talk to you
this morning

01:09:20.389 --> 01:09:22.458
about entrepreneurship
on the next frontier,

01:09:22.458 --> 01:09:23.792
but if you'll allow me,

01:09:23.792 --> 01:09:25.294
I'd like to spend
a couple of minutes

01:09:25.294 --> 01:09:28.697
showcasing the commercial
remote sensing example

01:09:28.697 --> 01:09:31.700
first from a perspective
of its promise, but secondly,

01:09:31.700 --> 01:09:33.502
from the continuing
challenges that we have.

01:09:33.502 --> 01:09:34.803
And some of them have
been mentioned already,

01:09:34.803 --> 01:09:36.305
and I'll go quickly over those.

01:09:38.507 --> 01:09:41.277
If you can imagine a traditional
intelligence analyst,

01:09:41.277 --> 01:09:42.878
or a scientist poring over

01:09:42.878 --> 01:09:45.614
a small number
of satellite images,

01:09:45.614 --> 01:09:47.516
you have a somewhat
outdated view of the world.

01:09:48.183 --> 01:09:50.085
American firms are at
the cutting edge

01:09:50.085 --> 01:09:52.555
of the global commercial
remote sensing market.

01:09:53.489 --> 01:09:55.724
They collect images
with high resolution,

01:09:55.724 --> 01:09:57.226
with increasing frequency,

01:09:57.793 --> 01:10:00.629
and create unprecedented
volumes of information.

01:10:01.530 --> 01:10:03.499
Other innovators
are harnessing machine

01:10:03.499 --> 01:10:06.368
learning and other advanced
analytic techniques

01:10:06.368 --> 01:10:09.338
to gain insight
into that industry imagery.

01:10:10.105 --> 01:10:12.975
And yet other potential
entrants to the market

01:10:12.975 --> 01:10:15.477
want to collect even more
exquisite satellite data,

01:10:16.178 --> 01:10:18.747
with other capabilities
like radio frequency data

01:10:18.747 --> 01:10:20.149
and social media.

01:10:20.149 --> 01:10:21.617
These American firms have access

01:10:21.617 --> 01:10:23.619
to world-class
satellite technology,

01:10:23.619 --> 01:10:25.254
and they're leveraging
breakthroughs

01:10:25.254 --> 01:10:27.523
and cloud computing
communications,

01:10:27.523 --> 01:10:29.592
artificial intelligence,
and visualization.

01:10:31.260 --> 01:10:34.096
Some analysts believe that
remote sensing-based insights

01:10:34.096 --> 01:10:37.032
will become as important
to commercial decision-making

01:10:37.566 --> 01:10:39.668
as accounting
and computing is today.

01:10:40.502 --> 01:10:43.372
In other words,
we cannot talk about space

01:10:43.372 --> 01:10:45.741
without talking
about the effects

01:10:45.741 --> 01:10:47.943
they're already
on the ground today.

01:10:48.744 --> 01:10:51.814
Other capabilities,
like 3D image processing

01:10:51.814 --> 01:10:54.850
and augmented reality create
breathtaking visualizations

01:10:54.850 --> 01:10:56.885
based on real-time data

01:10:56.885 --> 01:10:59.421
that create new levels
of interaction and exploration.

01:11:00.255 --> 01:11:02.825
As we move deeper
into the insights economy,

01:11:02.825 --> 01:11:04.994
commercial remote sensing
will play an extraordinary role

01:11:04.994 --> 01:11:07.129
in providing
detailed information

01:11:07.129 --> 01:11:09.064
about a wide range
of topics on the ground.

01:11:10.132 --> 01:11:11.734
We all know the old phrase,

01:11:11.734 --> 01:11:14.303
 A picture is worth
a thousand words. 

01:11:14.303 --> 01:11:17.206
Consider, then,
what a million pictures,

01:11:17.206 --> 01:11:20.242
richly detailed,
efficiently organized,

01:11:20.242 --> 01:11:23.012
time sequenced,
and thoroughly analyzed

01:11:23.012 --> 01:11:26.115
might mean for what
we understand about today,

01:11:26.115 --> 01:11:27.383
and even tomorrow.

01:11:28.217 --> 01:11:30.753
For the U.S. commercial
remote sensing industry,

01:11:30.753 --> 01:11:33.489
that's just one big step
on the way to the next frontier.

01:11:36.125 --> 01:11:37.793
Next year marks,
as has been said,

01:11:37.793 --> 01:11:40.462
the 25th anniversary of
the modern regulatory system

01:11:40.462 --> 01:11:41.697
for commercial remote sensing.

01:11:42.364 --> 01:11:44.266
While there has been
great progress,

01:11:44.266 --> 01:11:47.336
the process still hinders
the speed of U.S. innovation.

01:11:48.037 --> 01:11:50.039
First of all,
technological developments

01:11:50.039 --> 01:11:52.274
are outstripping our ability
to think about policy

01:11:52.274 --> 01:11:53.642
and regulatory developments.

01:11:54.243 --> 01:11:56.445
Much of the current
regulatory regime and outdated,

01:11:56.445 --> 01:11:58.714
reflecting, technology
and business processes

01:11:58.714 --> 01:12:00.449
from the early 2000s.

01:12:00.449 --> 01:12:02.751
Secondly, remote sensing impacts

01:12:02.751 --> 01:12:05.354
a very wide range of
U.S. government interests,

01:12:05.354 --> 01:12:07.556
from national security
and foreign policy,

01:12:07.556 --> 01:12:09.124
to agriculture and weather.

01:12:09.124 --> 01:12:12.194
Too many stakeholders delay
the licensing process,

01:12:12.194 --> 01:12:14.730
and as a result, sometimes
restricting companies

01:12:14.730 --> 01:12:18.033
from providing more advanced
remote sensing capabilities

01:12:18.033 --> 01:12:19.768
and the continuous
flow of data

01:12:19.768 --> 01:12:23.072
expected in today's
high-speed global markets

01:12:23.072 --> 01:12:26.942
in areas like agriculture,
finance, insurance, and others.

01:12:27.810 --> 01:12:29.578
Third, because satellite imagery

01:12:29.578 --> 01:12:32.481
is crucial to our nation's
defense and intelligence,

01:12:32.481 --> 01:12:34.183
it creates a level of caution

01:12:34.183 --> 01:12:36.719
that can slow or restrict
innovations to market.

01:12:37.319 --> 01:12:40.522
We know that commercialization
creates challenges

01:12:40.522 --> 01:12:42.424
for U.S. national security,

01:12:42.424 --> 01:12:46.462
but slowing down or delaying
commercial innovation

01:12:46.462 --> 01:12:48.530
is neither consistent
with U.S. policy,

01:12:49.031 --> 01:12:50.866
nor likely to be
a successful strategy.

01:12:51.800 --> 01:12:55.671
Commercial innovators face a
new kind of innovator's dilemma:

01:12:55.671 --> 01:12:57.773
those with the most
innovative ideas

01:12:57.773 --> 01:12:59.475
wait the longest time
for approval.

01:13:00.075 --> 01:13:02.678
As innovators languish
in the regulatory process,

01:13:02.678 --> 01:13:04.880
foreign competitors
can jump out

01:13:04.880 --> 01:13:06.949
and take advantage
of the original precedent.

01:13:07.850 --> 01:13:09.685
But now, many of the remedies
are well-known,

01:13:09.685 --> 01:13:11.053
and have been
discussed here today.

01:13:11.053 --> 01:13:12.621
The need to shorten
and hold accountable

01:13:12.621 --> 01:13:14.623
U.S. licensing time lines,

01:13:14.623 --> 01:13:16.125
the need to create
the presumption of yes

01:13:16.125 --> 01:13:18.694
in the licensing process,
and getting the elevation

01:13:18.694 --> 01:13:20.763
to the Cabinet level
of hard decisions.

01:13:21.764 --> 01:13:23.465
Regulation space-based
capabilities

01:13:23.465 --> 01:13:26.869
must also take into account
the other technologies

01:13:26.869 --> 01:13:28.103
that are coming forward
in the market,

01:13:28.103 --> 01:13:30.739
such as drones and
high-altitude air vehicles.

01:13:32.608 --> 01:13:34.877
In essence, remote sensing
is moving rapidly

01:13:34.877 --> 01:13:37.513
from a traditional
aerospace capability,

01:13:38.013 --> 01:13:40.382
affecting a small number
of important decisions

01:13:40.382 --> 01:13:42.518
to an information capability

01:13:42.518 --> 01:13:44.286
affecting thousands
of decisions,

01:13:44.286 --> 01:13:45.754
every single day.

01:13:45.754 --> 01:13:47.689
Even as we improve
the environment

01:13:47.689 --> 01:13:49.124
for U.S. commercial firms,

01:13:49.124 --> 01:13:52.461
a new slate of issues,
such as intellectual property,

01:13:52.461 --> 01:13:53.862
geospatial privacy,

01:13:54.396 --> 01:13:55.964
and foreign trade barriers

01:13:55.964 --> 01:13:58.167
will have to be incorporated
into our way of thinking.

01:13:59.635 --> 01:14:02.471
The 25-year case study
of commercial remote

01:14:02.471 --> 01:14:04.807
sensing provides important
lessons for how to think

01:14:04.807 --> 01:14:07.743
about the nation's broader
space commerce pursuits.

01:14:08.811 --> 01:14:10.512
We need to do a better job,
for example,

01:14:10.512 --> 01:14:13.482
of learning lessons
across the board areas

01:14:13.482 --> 01:14:15.884
like data rights, licensing,
and data protection.

01:14:16.451 --> 01:14:19.555
We also need to do a better job
of anticipating capabilities

01:14:19.555 --> 01:14:21.323
that are coming forward
in the market.

01:14:21.323 --> 01:14:23.158
This will allow for
early consideration

01:14:23.158 --> 01:14:26.195
of possible U.S. government
use and public policy impact.

01:14:26.728 --> 01:14:29.164
We've done well, for example,
in areas like non-Earth

01:14:29.164 --> 01:14:31.767
imaging and spatial
situational awareness.

01:14:32.434 --> 01:14:35.504
Finally, we need to encourage
strong, continuing collaboration

01:14:35.504 --> 01:14:37.639
between the U.S.
government and industry.

01:14:37.639 --> 01:14:40.509
We need to do a better job of
harnessing industry information

01:14:40.509 --> 01:14:42.177
on issues like
global competition,

01:14:42.711 --> 01:14:44.546
international
regulatory activities,

01:14:44.546 --> 01:14:46.114
and emerging sources
of innovation.

01:14:46.615 --> 01:14:49.918
The U.S. government cannot be
the only source of good ideas

01:14:49.918 --> 01:14:52.087
on how to regulate
on complex issues,

01:14:52.087 --> 01:14:54.456
like space debris,
or space traffic management.

01:14:55.591 --> 01:14:59.361
To close, U.S. government
and industry roles are changing

01:14:59.361 --> 01:15:02.331
so we do need to think
about new strategies

01:15:02.331 --> 01:15:04.633
to advance policy
and regulatory mechanisms

01:15:04.633 --> 01:15:06.735
to stay as close
to technology as possible.

01:15:07.436 --> 01:15:09.338
We recognize that
U.S. leadership

01:15:09.338 --> 01:15:12.241
is as much about shaping
the global environment,

01:15:12.241 --> 01:15:16.044
setting standards, encouraging
international partnerships,

01:15:16.044 --> 01:15:18.347
as it is about being
first in space,

01:15:18.347 --> 01:15:20.449
and in how we
ultimately use the data

01:15:20.449 --> 01:15:23.085
in thousands of applications
on the ground every day.

01:15:23.819 --> 01:15:26.288
As in so many other technology
innovation areas,

01:15:26.288 --> 01:15:31.393
both past and present, ours must
be a game of moving forward,

01:15:31.393 --> 01:15:32.961
not playing defense.

01:15:32.961 --> 01:15:34.663
Thank you, and I look
forward to your questions.

01:15:35.397 --> 01:15:36.732
The Vice President:
Great.

01:15:36.732 --> 01:15:38.667
Thank you, Kevin,
very well done.

01:15:38.667 --> 01:15:41.837
(Applause.)

01:15:41.837 --> 01:15:44.573
Tom Stroup, Satellite
Industry Association.

01:15:44.573 --> 01:15:46.141
Thank you for being with us.

01:15:46.141 --> 01:15:46.942
Mr. Stroup:
Mr. Vice President,

01:15:46.942 --> 01:15:48.644
the distinguished
members of the council,

01:15:48.644 --> 01:15:51.079
I'm honored to be here today
in this extraordinary venue.

01:15:51.813 --> 01:15:54.516
I'm Tom Stroup, president of the
Satellite Industry Association.

01:15:55.250 --> 01:15:57.719
SIA is a U.S.
based trade association

01:15:57.719 --> 01:16:00.222
representing the leading
satellite operators,

01:16:00.222 --> 01:16:03.926
manufacturers, launch providers,
and ground equipment suppliers.

01:16:04.426 --> 01:16:06.929
We serve commercial, civil,
and military markets.

01:16:07.629 --> 01:16:09.131
I would like to take
this opportunity

01:16:09.131 --> 01:16:11.233
to focus on three areas:

01:16:11.233 --> 01:16:13.635
innovation, spectrum certainty,

01:16:13.635 --> 01:16:15.604
and sustainable
space operations.

01:16:16.371 --> 01:16:21.243
Today, the satellite industry
supports over 211,000 U.S. jobs,

01:16:21.243 --> 01:16:22.878
including tens of thousands

01:16:22.878 --> 01:16:25.213
of well-paying
manufacturing positions.

01:16:25.881 --> 01:16:29.651
The satellite industry's
2017 estimated revenue

01:16:29.651 --> 01:16:31.820
was $260.5 billion,

01:16:32.788 --> 01:16:35.691
which does not reflect revenues
from the many businesses

01:16:35.691 --> 01:16:37.359
made possible
by our services.

01:16:38.260 --> 01:16:39.928
Satellites are
constantly operating

01:16:39.928 --> 01:16:41.330
in the background of space,

01:16:41.964 --> 01:16:43.799
enabling the American economy

01:16:43.799 --> 01:16:45.867
in ways consumers
might not be aware.

01:16:46.768 --> 01:16:48.503
Beyond strictly
financial metrics,

01:16:48.503 --> 01:16:51.573
however, our very way of life
depends on the benefits

01:16:51.573 --> 01:16:55.210
we receive from satellite-based
services and applications.

01:16:55.944 --> 01:16:59.648
Satellites, communications,
Earth observation,

01:16:59.648 --> 01:17:03.051
and position navigation
and timing have transformed

01:17:03.051 --> 01:17:04.653
how we communicate,

01:17:04.653 --> 01:17:06.989
how we map, navigate the world,
and see our world.

01:17:07.656 --> 01:17:10.425
How we produce food and energy,
conduct banking,

01:17:10.425 --> 01:17:11.593
predict the weather,

01:17:11.593 --> 01:17:14.129
ensure national security,
and so much more.

01:17:14.129 --> 01:17:16.732
The ubiquity of
satellite coverage

01:17:16.732 --> 01:17:19.267
provides access to areas
across the globe

01:17:19.267 --> 01:17:20.802
that are otherwise unreachable.

01:17:21.603 --> 01:17:24.306
Satellites provide
telecommunication services

01:17:24.306 --> 01:17:27.242
to U.S. citizens
from those in rural regions

01:17:27.242 --> 01:17:29.511
without terrestrial
internet access

01:17:29.511 --> 01:17:31.546
to scientists at the South Pole,

01:17:31.546 --> 01:17:34.750
and have proven critical in
areas of natural disasters,

01:17:34.750 --> 01:17:36.618
such as the
hurricane-stricken areas,

01:17:36.618 --> 01:17:39.121
such as Puerto Rico and Virgin
-- and the Virgin Islands.

01:17:40.155 --> 01:17:43.759
Satellite imagery is also
critical for disaster response,

01:17:43.759 --> 01:17:45.961
allowing for
the surveying of damage,

01:17:45.961 --> 01:17:48.330
not just by emergency
management officials,

01:17:48.330 --> 01:17:50.465
but by average citizens
from across the globe.

01:17:51.533 --> 01:17:53.068
All of the breakthroughs
we've seen

01:17:53.068 --> 01:17:54.803
because of satellite technology

01:17:54.803 --> 01:17:56.204
should not be taken for granted.

01:17:56.805 --> 01:17:58.473
They depend upon our ability,

01:17:58.473 --> 01:18:00.809
our industry's ability
to access spectrum.

01:18:01.610 --> 01:18:02.978
In order to sustain

01:18:02.978 --> 01:18:04.212
and meet the growing demand

01:18:04.212 --> 01:18:05.914
for satellite services,

01:18:05.914 --> 01:18:08.417
we encourage regulators
to continue to allocate

01:18:08.417 --> 01:18:10.452
sufficient spectrum
for satellite use,

01:18:10.986 --> 01:18:13.488
both domestically
and via U.S. support

01:18:13.488 --> 01:18:16.992
at the upcoming world radio
communications conference.

01:18:17.893 --> 01:18:19.194
Regulatory streaming --

01:18:19.194 --> 01:18:21.830
streamlining uncertainty
also are critical

01:18:21.830 --> 01:18:24.566
for the advancement of new
technologies in the industry.

01:18:25.267 --> 01:18:28.437
With plans to launch satellite
constellations of hundreds,

01:18:28.437 --> 01:18:31.606
if not thousands of satellites
over the next decade,

01:18:31.606 --> 01:18:35.844
it is crucial that regulation be
adaptable to new technologies.

01:18:36.878 --> 01:18:39.347
Finally, sustainable
development also --

01:18:39.347 --> 01:18:41.450
must also be at the heart
of innovations

01:18:41.450 --> 01:18:43.485
and advancements
of the satellite industry.

01:18:44.086 --> 01:18:46.054
As a shared natural resource,

01:18:46.054 --> 01:18:49.224
it is our responsibility
to protect space

01:18:49.224 --> 01:18:52.461
and ensure its availability
for use by future generations.

01:18:52.961 --> 01:18:54.596
Thank you, and I look
forward to your questions.

01:18:55.831 --> 01:18:56.731
The Vice President:
Thank you very much.

01:18:56.731 --> 01:18:58.667
(Applause.)

01:18:58.667 --> 01:19:01.236
Well done, Tom, appreciate it.

01:19:02.237 --> 01:19:04.439
Mary Lynne Dittmar
is with the Coalition

01:19:05.140 --> 01:19:07.008
for Deep Space Exploration,

01:19:07.008 --> 01:19:09.177
and we're grateful for you here.

01:19:10.112 --> 01:19:11.780
Dr. Dittmar:
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

01:19:11.780 --> 01:19:13.281
Members of the National
Space Council,

01:19:13.281 --> 01:19:14.749
Executive Secretary Pace,

01:19:14.749 --> 01:19:17.285
thank you for inviting me
to speak on entrepreneurship

01:19:17.285 --> 01:19:18.553
and economic expansion

01:19:18.553 --> 01:19:20.255
of the new frontier.

01:19:20.255 --> 01:19:22.424
Entrepreneurial risk-taking
and innovation are,

01:19:22.424 --> 01:19:25.727
without doubt, engines for
economic development in space,

01:19:26.361 --> 01:19:28.763
beginning in low Earth orbit,
and expanding toward the moon.

01:19:29.564 --> 01:19:31.466
At the same time,
government programs,

01:19:31.466 --> 01:19:34.102
such as the Space Launch System,
the crew vehicle Orion,

01:19:34.636 --> 01:19:37.339
and the ground systems necessary
to support both government

01:19:37.339 --> 01:19:40.075
and industry provide
much-needed infrastructure

01:19:40.075 --> 01:19:41.443
for further
economic development.

01:19:42.244 --> 01:19:43.712
Even more importantly,

01:19:43.712 --> 01:19:45.747
they maintain national
constancy of purpose

01:19:45.747 --> 01:19:48.650
as a signal to other governments
of the U.S. commitment

01:19:48.650 --> 01:19:50.719
to leadership in space.

01:19:50.719 --> 01:19:52.254
As has already been discussed,

01:19:52.254 --> 01:19:54.623
the nature of the policy
and regulatory framework

01:19:54.623 --> 01:19:57.759
guiding our collective issue --
collective efforts is crucial.

01:19:58.493 --> 01:20:01.263
I would like to address the
third trail acquisition reform.

01:20:02.330 --> 01:20:05.433
The fiscal programmatic
reporting and management burdens

01:20:05.433 --> 01:20:07.736
associated with
the often-glacial pace

01:20:07.736 --> 01:20:10.739
of traditional contracting
can hardly be overstated.

01:20:10.739 --> 01:20:12.340
As an aside when
I was asked by a member

01:20:12.340 --> 01:20:14.009
of the presidential
transition team

01:20:14.009 --> 01:20:17.012
what single thing could most
advance exploration of space,

01:20:17.012 --> 01:20:18.513
my answer was far 2.0.

01:20:20.182 --> 01:20:24.019
Of more importance, even alarm
at the slow nature of government

01:20:24.019 --> 01:20:27.155
procurements creates barriers
to technological advancement,

01:20:27.155 --> 01:20:29.391
posing a threat to
our national security

01:20:29.391 --> 01:20:30.625
and our leadership in space.

01:20:31.560 --> 01:20:33.562
This is not to say
that traditional contracting

01:20:33.562 --> 01:20:35.063
should be abandoned.

01:20:35.063 --> 01:20:36.831
For example, cost-plus contacts

01:20:36.831 --> 01:20:38.934
for managing large-scale
development programs

01:20:38.934 --> 01:20:41.069
provide stability,
reduce industry risk,

01:20:41.069 --> 01:20:43.972
and ensure sustainment
of the U.S. industrial base

01:20:43.972 --> 01:20:46.174
over the years or decades
that are often required

01:20:46.174 --> 01:20:47.742
for these programs.

01:20:47.742 --> 01:20:50.412
That said, the means to leave
the starting gate

01:20:50.412 --> 01:20:53.181
with far more agility
than currently exists,

01:20:53.181 --> 01:20:55.917
as well as renewed mechanisms
for accountability

01:20:55.917 --> 01:20:57.185
and constraints on schedule

01:20:57.185 --> 01:21:00.121
and cost growth are of
primary interest and reform.

01:21:01.456 --> 01:21:03.525
Other Transactional
Agreements, or OTAs,

01:21:03.525 --> 01:21:04.793
represent a different approach

01:21:04.793 --> 01:21:06.194
not subject to the oversight

01:21:06.194 --> 01:21:07.462
required of federal contracts.

01:21:08.096 --> 01:21:10.665
OTAs provide flexibility,
but also increased

01:21:10.665 --> 01:21:13.068
risk of reduced accountability
and transparency.

01:21:13.902 --> 01:21:15.804
For this reason,
the vast majority of them

01:21:15.804 --> 01:21:17.205
are relatively low value.

01:21:17.706 --> 01:21:19.040
Notable exceptions include

01:21:19.040 --> 01:21:20.875
the Commercial Orbital
Transportation System,

01:21:20.875 --> 01:21:23.712
or COTS, and the Commercial Crew
Development Program,

01:21:23.712 --> 01:21:25.947
both at NASA.
During COTS,

01:21:25.947 --> 01:21:28.316
the government invested a
substantial amount of the cost,

01:21:28.316 --> 01:21:30.852
and left development in the
hands of private enterprise.

01:21:31.620 --> 01:21:33.054
The resulting systems
were developed

01:21:33.054 --> 01:21:34.689
at much less cost
to the government

01:21:34.689 --> 01:21:36.958
than a traditional cost-plus
contract would have achieved.

01:21:37.692 --> 01:21:40.362
The story is less clear
with crude systems, however,

01:21:40.362 --> 01:21:42.931
wherein the balance between
contractor discretion,

01:21:42.931 --> 01:21:43.965
government insight,

01:21:43.965 --> 01:21:46.167
and the risk to human lives
continues to be debated.

01:21:47.235 --> 01:21:49.137
I turn next to public-private
partnerships,

01:21:49.137 --> 01:21:53.675
or P3s, which have advanced
both the A and the S in NASA --

01:21:53.675 --> 01:21:55.443
Aeronautics and Space.

01:21:55.443 --> 01:21:58.847
P3s take many forms: subsidies,
government-backed loans,

01:21:58.847 --> 01:22:01.449
government-owned contractor
operated entities,

01:22:01.449 --> 01:22:03.785
repurposing of public assets,
just to name a few.

01:22:04.519 --> 01:22:08.189
The success of P3s hinges
on informed allocation of risk

01:22:08.189 --> 01:22:10.058
to each side of the partnership.

01:22:10.992 --> 01:22:12.794
A realistic business case,

01:22:12.794 --> 01:22:14.696
which is an indispensable
requirement,

01:22:15.563 --> 01:22:17.699
and a means
to incentivize business

01:22:17.699 --> 01:22:20.568
to align private objectives
with the public interest.

01:22:21.436 --> 01:22:24.606
As a path forward into deep
space, P3s carry much promise.

01:22:25.206 --> 01:22:27.709
But as on Earth, they require
a carefully thought out set

01:22:27.709 --> 01:22:30.712
of requirements,
processes, and objectives.

01:22:31.946 --> 01:22:35.583
Each of these models attempts
to balance risk discretion,

01:22:35.583 --> 01:22:39.120
cost incentives, and mission
objectives in different ways.

01:22:40.088 --> 01:22:41.823
I cannot say
this strongly enough:

01:22:42.457 --> 01:22:44.726
decisions regarding
which approach is best

01:22:44.726 --> 01:22:46.061
for a given objective

01:22:46.061 --> 01:22:48.396
cannot be driven by ideology,

01:22:48.396 --> 01:22:50.332
whether political
or philosophical.

01:22:51.199 --> 01:22:53.201
Rather, an acquisition framework

01:22:53.201 --> 01:22:55.804
that drives successful program
development and execution

01:22:56.338 --> 01:22:59.741
encourages private investment
and market-driven solutions,

01:22:59.741 --> 01:23:01.343
and maintains
the ability to adapt

01:23:01.343 --> 01:23:03.712
to always-changing
external realities

01:23:03.712 --> 01:23:05.513
should be our
collective goal.

01:23:05.513 --> 01:23:07.515
Thank you.

01:23:07.515 --> 01:23:13.722
(Applause.)

01:23:13.722 --> 01:23:14.556
The Vice President:
Thank you, Mary Lynne.

01:23:14.556 --> 01:23:15.990
Very well done.

01:23:15.990 --> 01:23:20.628
And let me -- let me maybe
ask a question of the panel.

01:23:21.329 --> 01:23:24.666
I have a feeling
I'm going to get word

01:23:24.666 --> 01:23:28.837
that we need to be moving
to our next appointment.

01:23:28.837 --> 01:23:34.142
But maybe I could start
with you, Dr. Dittmar, that --

01:23:34.142 --> 01:23:36.544
given your extensive experience
on the Space Station,

01:23:37.045 --> 01:23:42.183
the President has announced
our plan to transition

01:23:42.183 --> 01:23:43.685
to a different model

01:23:44.652 --> 01:23:46.921
for America's presence
in low-Earth orbit.

01:23:46.921 --> 01:23:51.292
One of our previous
panelists said --

01:23:51.292 --> 01:23:53.261
I thought, rather insightfully,

01:23:53.261 --> 01:23:56.698
where we would transition
the government

01:23:56.698 --> 01:24:00.835
to more tenant and customer,
rather than landlord,

01:24:02.170 --> 01:24:05.607
so that we could focus
on human exploration,

01:24:06.741 --> 01:24:08.810
and pushing the boundaries.

01:24:08.810 --> 01:24:11.546
Can -- since you all
represent this industry,

01:24:12.280 --> 01:24:15.617
could each of you maybe give me
one minute on where the --

01:24:17.652 --> 01:24:19.788
where are the opportunities,
where are the challenges?

01:24:19.788 --> 01:24:21.156
What should this council
be aware of,

01:24:21.156 --> 01:24:23.458
as we seek to make
that transition?

01:24:23.458 --> 01:24:25.226
And Dr. Dittmar,
on the Space Station, you've --

01:24:26.327 --> 01:24:28.096
I've forgotten more about it
than I'll ever learn.

01:24:28.096 --> 01:24:29.397
Dr. Dittmar:
So, I'll start by saying

01:24:29.397 --> 01:24:32.200
that the demands side

01:24:33.501 --> 01:24:36.604
is as important as
the supply side, in this case.

01:24:37.739 --> 01:24:39.908
So, developing --
finding additional ways

01:24:39.908 --> 01:24:40.875
that have already
been discussed,

01:24:40.875 --> 01:24:43.578
but many other ways to
encourage demand, to develop --

01:24:43.578 --> 01:24:45.580
especially in low-Earth orbit
is critical.

01:24:45.580 --> 01:24:47.582
I think we also need
to establish some criteria

01:24:47.582 --> 01:24:49.384
for that transition.

01:24:49.384 --> 01:24:50.752
Those should include readiness

01:24:50.752 --> 01:24:53.087
to assume role of
the commercial industry,

01:24:53.087 --> 01:24:54.489
and there are certainly
a number of efforts

01:24:54.489 --> 01:24:55.824
that are under way right now.

01:24:55.824 --> 01:24:57.792
A clear strategy
for continued expanded

01:24:57.792 --> 01:24:59.027
international collaboration,

01:24:59.027 --> 01:25:00.061
both in low-Earth orbit

01:25:00.061 --> 01:25:02.330
and then toward the moon
is very important.

01:25:02.330 --> 01:25:04.599
The framework that guided
the development of the station

01:25:04.599 --> 01:25:06.367
has enabled everything
that's happened there,

01:25:06.367 --> 01:25:08.503
and I think that's critical.

01:25:08.503 --> 01:25:10.505
A plan for ensuring
that critical exploration

01:25:10.505 --> 01:25:12.273
technologies can continue
to be developed.

01:25:12.273 --> 01:25:15.276
So, for example, environmental
control is very important.

01:25:15.276 --> 01:25:18.446
Astronauts like to breathe
they're in deep space.

01:25:18.446 --> 01:25:20.682
So, we need to make sure
that we have a working system

01:25:20.682 --> 01:25:22.083
that will enable
that over a long period

01:25:22.083 --> 01:25:23.318
of time in deep space.

01:25:23.318 --> 01:25:25.286
And then, the nature
of the vehicle itself.

01:25:26.154 --> 01:25:28.156
You know, what is it capable of?

01:25:28.156 --> 01:25:29.491
What is the follow-on
capable of?

01:25:29.491 --> 01:25:31.259
Sort of what do we want to do
with it, going forward?

01:25:31.259 --> 01:25:32.160
The Vice President:
Good, good insights.

01:25:32.160 --> 01:25:33.928
Anyone else?
Just a quick shot on --

01:25:34.629 --> 01:25:35.463
Mr. Stroup:
Just very quickly --

01:25:35.463 --> 01:25:37.131
The Vice President:
Tom?

01:25:37.131 --> 01:25:38.800
Mr. Stroup: -- I would also 
address procurement reform because --

01:25:38.800 --> 01:25:40.435
because I think very often,

01:25:40.435 --> 01:25:43.204
as the military is large
customer of the industry,

01:25:43.204 --> 01:25:46.007
making a transition
from viewing themselves

01:25:46.007 --> 01:25:48.643
as purchasing satellites to
purchasing services in addition

01:25:48.643 --> 01:25:52.213
to the unique satellites
that they have a specific need.

01:25:52.213 --> 01:25:55.650
But looking at how they can
acquire satellite services

01:25:55.650 --> 01:25:56.851
more quickly would be important.

01:25:57.418 --> 01:25:59.287
The Vice President:
Great, Kevin, Eric?

01:26:00.154 --> 01:26:01.389
Mr. O'Connell:
Just briefly, I think

01:26:01.389 --> 01:26:03.224
anticipating the kinds
of capabilities

01:26:03.224 --> 01:26:05.059
that are coming forth
in the market --

01:26:05.059 --> 01:26:07.462
paying explicit attention
to U.S. government use,

01:26:07.462 --> 01:26:09.797
to public policy concerns,
et cetera,

01:26:09.797 --> 01:26:12.000
it's something that needs
to be done proactively,

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:13.434
not wait until people show up

01:26:13.434 --> 01:26:15.036
with a new capability
for licensing.

01:26:17.205 --> 01:26:18.006
Mr. Stallmer:
And I think,

01:26:18.006 --> 01:26:19.207
just to touch on
what Mary Lynne said,

01:26:19.207 --> 01:26:22.143
you know, the idea of having
a smooth transition plan,

01:26:22.143 --> 01:26:23.411
avoiding any kind of gap,

01:26:23.945 --> 01:26:26.481
and really utilizing
a lot of the innovation

01:26:26.481 --> 01:26:29.150
and the technology that the
commercial industry is driven --

01:26:29.150 --> 01:26:32.487
is driving right now,
whether it be through habitat --

01:26:32.487 --> 01:26:33.955
you know, habitat modules,

01:26:33.955 --> 01:26:35.857
or you know, new
transportation systems,

01:26:35.857 --> 01:26:38.660
or just the experiments
that are taking place

01:26:38.660 --> 01:26:39.861
on the International
Space Station.

01:26:39.861 --> 01:26:42.697
I think it's -- there's
remarkable technologies

01:26:42.697 --> 01:26:44.299
that are being developed
at a rapid pace,

01:26:44.299 --> 01:26:45.600
and we want to
incorporate them

01:26:45.600 --> 01:26:47.502
throughout the process
of this transition.

01:26:48.036 --> 01:26:50.305
The Vice President:
Great, that's great.

01:26:50.305 --> 01:26:52.774
Join me in thanking
this outstanding panel.

01:26:52.774 --> 01:26:54.976
Great insights,
great overview.

01:26:54.976 --> 01:26:57.545
Thank you so much, great job.

01:26:57.545 --> 01:27:01.316
(Applause.)

01:27:01.316 --> 01:27:03.885
Well, the members of
the National Space Council,

01:27:03.885 --> 01:27:06.087
I think this has been
a great discussion.

01:27:06.087 --> 01:27:11.059
Before we adjourn, I'd like
to task a few items to assign

01:27:11.793 --> 01:27:13.661
to Administrator Lightfoot.

01:27:14.796 --> 01:27:17.966
I appreciate you working
with Commerce and State

01:27:17.966 --> 01:27:23.438
to develop a strategy
to develop the framework

01:27:23.438 --> 01:27:24.739
for great cooperation

01:27:24.739 --> 01:27:26.674
with our private
sector partners.

01:27:28.009 --> 01:27:33.081
And as appropriate,
international partners as well.

01:27:34.716 --> 01:27:35.917
And we'd --

01:27:35.917 --> 01:27:40.054
I'd welcome your recommendations
by our meetings

01:27:40.054 --> 01:27:42.624
this fall that we could forward
to the President

01:27:42.624 --> 01:27:45.627
in the form of
a decision memorandum.

01:27:45.627 --> 01:27:47.895
And we already --

01:27:47.895 --> 01:27:52.867
I think we touched
on a number of issues

01:27:52.867 --> 01:27:54.535
in the previous
recommendation,

01:27:54.535 --> 01:27:56.204
but this panel's been
a great affirmation,

01:27:56.204 --> 01:27:58.406
I think, of
the overall direction,

01:27:58.406 --> 01:28:00.174
but we'll take your
steady council on this,

01:28:00.174 --> 01:28:02.110
on an ongoing basis.

01:28:02.110 --> 01:28:04.779
With that, let me thank
all the members

01:28:06.114 --> 01:28:08.316
of the National Space Council,

01:28:08.316 --> 01:28:11.185
especially the members
of the Cabinet who are here.

01:28:11.986 --> 01:28:14.455
Distinguished members
of the user advisory group,

01:28:14.455 --> 01:28:16.424
I encourage all of you
that have an interest

01:28:16.424 --> 01:28:18.860
in the work of
the National Space Council

01:28:18.860 --> 01:28:22.430
to avail yourself of
the extraordinary women and men

01:28:22.430 --> 01:28:25.867
who have stepped forward
to offer advice and counsel

01:28:26.768 --> 01:28:29.837
to the work of
the National Space Council.

01:28:29.837 --> 01:28:34.008
I want to thank
the extraordinary men

01:28:34.008 --> 01:28:36.944
and women of
the Kennedy Space Center

01:28:37.545 --> 01:28:39.914
for their hospitality

01:28:39.914 --> 01:28:42.750
and to each
and every one of you,

01:28:42.750 --> 01:28:45.420
thank you for your
great interest in this.

01:28:45.420 --> 01:28:47.388
The work will continue,

01:28:47.388 --> 01:28:50.058
and America is leading
in space again,

01:28:50.692 --> 01:28:51.893
thanks to all of you, thank you.

01:28:51.893 --> 01:28:53.294
God bless you,
it's good to be with you all.

01:28:53.294 --> 01:28:54.395
(Applause.)

